  ('D-003','Trekking','Pure endurance',NULL,'2–3 weeks unloaded. For AR: begin loaded hiking Week 1 at 15–20 lb; escalate to race weight by Week 6–8.',2,3,'BASE: 3–5 wks (15–20 lb pack, moderate terrain) BUILD: 5–8 wks (progressive pack weight + duration, varied terrain) PEAK: 2–4 wks (full race-weight pack, race-duration hikes) TAPER: 1–2 wks','Volume (hrs): max 10–15%/week Pack weight: add max 5 lb/week Do NOT increase both pack weight AND duration in same week.','45–54: Max 3–4 lb/week weight increase; 72 hrs recovery between long hikes. 55+: Max 2–3 lb/week. Alternate long-hike days with bike or paddle recovery.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks Volume cut: 30–40% Maintain pack weight — taper duration, not weight',ARRAY['Hip flexor strain','Lower back strain','Blisters','Knee pain (descents)','Shoulder/trap fatigue'],ARRAY['Jumping to race weight without progression','Poor pack fit','Long descents before eccentric conditioning','New footwear on first long hike'],'1. Leg elevation (10–15 min post-hike) 2. CWI lower body after descents 3. Blister/foot care (practical priority) 4. Carb resynthesis within 60 min 5. Sleep',ARRAY['Leg elevation (10–15 min post-hike) 2. CWI lower body after descents 3. Blister/foot care (practical priority) 4. Carb resynthesis within 60 min 5. Sleep'],'CWI for eccentric loading: Strong Pack progression: Practitioner consensus (AR coaching, military literature)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-004','Swimming','Pure endurance',NULL,'4–6 weeks pool technique base before open-water work (sighting, navigation, mass start, current, chop). Total beginners: 8–12 weeks before structured open water training.  Triathlon note: swimming is the first discipline — arrives at T1 with swim fatigue. This is physically non-taxing for the bike (upper body fatigue, legs fresh) but the water→land transition itself is disorienting.',4,6,'BASE: 4–6 wks (pool technique — catch, drive, exit, bilateral breathing; form over volume) BUILD: 6–8 wks (open water integration, sighting practice, intervals on erg or pool, 1–2 open water sessions/week) PEAK: 3–4 wks (wetsuit-specific sessions, mass start simulation, race-pace sets, T1 transition practice) TAPER: 1–2 wks (cut volume 40–50%, maintain open water feel)  SPECIFIC TO TRIATHLON: Drafting in swim (draft-legal: position behind another swimmer''s feet) reduces energy expenditure by estimated 6–10% — practice in pool.','10–15%/week increase in yardage. Open water sessions: add 1×/week per 2-week block.  PADDLE USE CAUTION: Regular use of swim paddles significantly associated with higher overuse shoulder injury rate in triathletes (p=0.014, PMC5983428). Limit paddle use to 1×/week maximum; never paddle hard sets on consecutive days.','45+: Limit hard pull sets; monitor rotator cuff. Paddle use especially risky above 40 given slower tendon recovery. 55+: Max 2 hard swim sessions/week. Focus on technique over volume — swim returns diminish faster at age than bike/run aerobic capacity.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks Volume cut: 40–50% Maintain 2–3 swims/week at reduced volume (pool OK) Wetsuit: wear in final 2–3 swims pre-race if race is wetsuit-legal',ARRAY['Swimmer''s Shoulder (rotator cuff impingement — most common swim injury)
Neck strain (sighting frequency — head lift extension)
Elbow / tricep tendinopathy (heavy pull set volume)
Shoulder overuse (paddle use — higher rate, statistically significant)

NOTE: Swimming has the lowest injury incidence of the three triathlon disciplines (5–11%, systematic review PMC8884864) — this is the cross-training advantage of swim volume'],ARRAY['High-volume pull set training','Regular paddle use (statistically significant risk factor — PMC5983428)','Poor catch mechanics (dropped elbow = shoulder impingement risk)','Sighting too frequently (neck extension load)','Rapid yardage increase in first training month'],'1. Sleep 2. Shoulder-specific: cross-body stretch + posterior capsule stretch post-session 3. CWI upper body (forearms/shoulders) if tendinopathy developing 4. Rotator cuff antagonist work (external rotation with band — counterbalance to internal rotation dominance in freestyle) 5. Wrist extensor stretch (complements catch mechanics)  NOTE: Swimming itself acts as recovery for running and cycling — use swim sessions as active recovery on high-load days',ARRAY['Sleep 2. Shoulder-specific: cross-body stretch + posterior capsule stretch post-session 3. CWI upper body (forearms/shoulders) if tendinopathy developing 4. Rotator cuff antagonist work (external rotation with band — counterbalance to internal rotation dominance in freestyle) 5. Wrist extensor stretch (complements catch mechanics)  NOTE: Swimming itself acts as recovery for running and cycling — use swim sessions as active recovery on high-load days'],'Swimmer''s shoulder research: Moderate-Strong (aquatic sports medicine) Paddle use → shoulder overuse: Strong — statistically significant in triathlete-specific cohort (PMC5983428) Swim as lowest-injury discipline: Strong (systematic review PMC8884864) Drafting benefit: Moderate (coaching literature consensus, mechanistically supported)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-006','Road Cycling','Pure endurance',NULL,'No hard minimum — road cycling is low-impact relative to running. 2–3 weeks Zone 2 before structured intervals. Athletes with running base: aerobic capacity transfers; cycling-specific muscle recruitment and saddle tolerance still require buildup.',2,3,'BASE: 4–8 wks (Zone 2 aerobic, cadence work 85–95 rpm, long rides — no intervals) BUILD: 6–8 wks (sweet spot 88–93% FTP, threshold intervals 95–105% FTP, longer rides with fueling rehearsal) PEAK: 3–4 wks (race-pace efforts, brick sessions — Bike→Run mandatory for triathlon) TAPER: 1–2 wks (volume cut 40–50%, maintain 2 intensity sessions)  TRIATHLON-SPECIFIC: Cycling is the longest discipline by time in all formats (48% of training time, Andersen et al. 2013). Cycling is the best predictor of overall performance in Sprint and 70.3 events (PMC8131838). Aerobic cycling base is the primary performance lever — don''t sacrifice it for run or swim volume.','10–15%/week ride hours. FTP intervals: increase 1 rep or 5% duration per 2-week block — not both simultaneously. Total training load ACWR: cycling volume is high enough that it can spike total ACWR even if run/swim look fine — monitor combined load.','40–44: Standard ramp; watch patellar tendon — most common cycling knee overuse. 45–54: 10%/week max; 2 easy days per week in build. 55+: 8%/week; saddle fit check early in the plan — saddle sores accumulate faster and persist longer.',NULL,10.0,8.0,'1–2 weeks Volume cut: 40–50% Maintain 2 intensity sessions (shorter) Bike fit check before taper — make NO changes in final 2 weeks',ARRAY['Knee pain (patellar tendon, IT band from cycling-specific mechanism)
Lower back pain (hip flexor tightness; aero position compounds this)
Neck/shoulder tension (head position — especially severe in aero/TT position)
Saddle sores (prolonged duration)
Achilles tendinopathy (cleat position)
Numbness (hands, feet — contact pressure)

AERO/TT BIKE ADDITIONAL: Cervical spine strain (sustained head-raised position in aero), hip flexor compression (forward seat position restricts hip angle), lower back strain (flat-back position requires hamstring flexibility not needed on road bike)'],ARRAY['Rapid intensity escalation without aerobic base','Poor saddle height (too high = Achilles, too low = patellar)','Poor cleat alignment (knee tracking)','No hip flexor stretching off bike','TT/Aero position without progressive adaptation (jumping straight into aggressive aero increases neck/back injury risk significantly)','Regular paddles (if also swimming — see D-004)'],'1. Active recovery spin (Zone 1, 20–30 min) — most effective for cycling-specific lactate clearance 2. Hip flexor stretching (non-negotiable post-ride for cyclists, especially in aero position) 3. CWI for interval days (11–15°C, 10–15 min) 4. Carb resynthesis (1–1.2 g/kg within 30–60 min) if second session same day or next morning 5. Neck stretches (flexion, extension, rotation — especially after aero sessions) 5. Sleep',ARRAY['Active recovery spin (Zone 1, 20–30 min) — most effective for cycling-specific lactate clearance 2. Hip flexor stretching (non-negotiable post-ride for cyclists, especially in aero position) 3. CWI for interval days (11–15°C, 10–15 min) 4. Carb resynthesis (1–1.2 g/kg within 30–60 min) if second session same day or next morning 5. Neck stretches (flexion, extension, rotation — especially after aero sessions) 5. Sleep'],'Active recovery for cycling: Strong Bike fit → injury prevention: Strong consensus (sports medicine + fitting literature) Aero position → neck/lower back: Strong practitioner consensus, moderate research Cycling as performance predictor in Sprint/70.3: Strong (PMC8131838, n=16,667) Paddle use risk (cross-discipline): Strong (PMC5983428)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-008','Mountain Biking','Mixed',NULL,'4–6 weeks road cycling for aerobic base and pedaling mechanics before technical trail riding.',4,6,'BASE: 4–6 wks (road or easy trail, pedaling efficiency, basic skills) BUILD: 6–8 wks (trail volume, technical skill sessions, progressive features) PEAK: 3–4 wks (race-specific sim, loaded sections, B2B riding) TAPER: 1–2 wks (maintain 1 technical skills session)','10–15%/week ride hours. Technical skill progression: add one new element per 2-week block (not by volume). CNS cap: max 2 hard technical sessions/week.','40–44: Max 2 hard MTB/week; monitor reaction time. 45–54: 1 hard + 1 moderate technical/week; 36–48 hr CNS recovery. 55+: 1 hard + 1 technique/week; road base volume should exceed trail.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks Volume cut: 35–50% Maintain 1 technical skills session',ARRAY['Lower back pain','Knee pain (fit)','Hand/wrist numbness','Shoulder impingement','Crashes (collarbone, shoulder)'],ARRAY['Skipping road base phase','Riding technically while fatigued','Poor bike fit','Insufficient core strength'],'1. Thoracic spine + lat foam roll (every MTB session) 2. Sleep 3. Hip flexor stretch 4. Shoulder cross-body stretch',ARRAY['Thoracic spine + lat foam roll (every MTB session) 2. Sleep 3. Hip flexor stretch 4. Shoulder cross-body stretch'],'MTB skill progression: Practitioner consensus CNS fatigue from technical MTB: Practitioner consensus (limited direct research)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-009','Packrafting','Mixed',NULL,'4–6 weeks flat-water paddle technique. Grip and shoulder tendon base critical — do not rush.',4,6,'BASE: 3–5 wks (technique, flat water, erg OK) BUILD: 5–8 wks (volume, interval sessions, river reading basics) PEAK: 2–3 wks (race sim, transitions, night paddling) TAPER: 1–2 wks','10–15%/week paddle hours. Grip sessions: max 3×/week regardless of fitness — tendons lag muscle by 4–8 wks.','45–54: Max 2 hard sessions/week; 48–72 hr shoulder recovery. 55+: 1 hard + 1 technique/week.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks Volume cut: 40–50% Maintain transition drill practice',ARRAY['Rotator cuff tendinitis','Lateral epicondylitis (elbow)','Lower back strain','Wrist tendinitis','Bicep tendinopathy'],ARRAY['Arm-dominant paddling','Rapid volume increase','Cold water without warmup','Gripping too tight','Mismatched paddle length'],'1. Wrist/forearm stretching after every session 2. Sleep 3. Local forearm CWI (11–15°C, 10 min) for tendinopathy 4. Collagen + Vit C pre-session (15g + 50mg, tendon support)',ARRAY['Wrist/forearm stretching after every session 2. Sleep 3. Local forearm CWI (11–15°C, 10 min) for tendinopathy 4. Collagen + Vit C pre-session (15g + 50mg, tendon support)'],'Paddle injury patterns: Moderate (kayak/canoe literature extrapolated) Collagen + Vit C: Emerging (Shaw et al. 2017)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-010','Kayaking','Pure endurance',NULL,'Same as packrafting: 4–6 weeks flat-water base. Develops paddle stroke mechanics, aerobic system, and seated endurance. Covers lake, calm river, and ocean / sea kayaking (touring and distance variants).',4,6,'Same structure as packrafting: BASE: Flat water technique BUILD: Volume + moving water introduction PEAK: Race-sim sustained paddle TAPER: 1–2 wks','Same as packrafting: 10–15%/week; grip sessions max 3×/week.','Same as packrafting by age group.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks Volume cut: 40–50%',ARRAY['Shoulder impingement / rotator cuff (bilateral overuse)','Wrist tendinopathy (paddle grip)','Lower back (seated position)','Blistered hands (grip)'],ARRAY['More than 3 hard paddle sessions/week','Neglecting shoulder antagonist work','Inadequate buildup of seated paddle endurance'],'Shoulder rotator cuff external rotation work. Wrist extensor stretch. Hip flexor stretch (seated paddling position).',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'Kayak injury patterns: Moderate (kayak-specific sports medicine literature)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-011','Canoeing','Pure endurance',NULL,'Same as kayaking: 4–6 weeks flat-water technique.',4,6,'Same structure as kayaking. Add partner coordination sessions from Week 1 if team paddling.','Same as kayaking: 10–15%/week; partner synchronization is a performance variable — train with race teammate.','Same as kayaking by age group.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks. Maintain partner coordination sessions.',ARRAY['Same shoulder/wrist/elbow patterns as kayaking, plus: lower back strain (rotational mismatch between partners)'],ARRAY['Not practicing with actual race partner','Mismatched paddle lengths'],'Same as kayaking.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'Canoeing-specific AR data: Limited — extrapolated from kayak literature',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-012','Rock Climbing','Technical-dominant',NULL,'8–12 weeks grip base (dead hangs, pull-ups) before technical loading. Non-negotiable minimum — finger tendons adapt 4–8 wks behind muscle.',8,12,'BASE: 6–10 wks (dead hangs, scapular pulls, antagonist work, grip) BUILD: 6–8 wks (route-specific movement, lock-offs, footwork) PEAK: 3–4 wks (full system: climb + rappel + pack) TAPER: 1–2 wks','Max 10%/week in hold time or route length. Hard sessions: max 2×/week regardless of phase.','45+: Max 2 sessions/week; avoid hard crimping. 55+: 1 hard + 1 technique/week; prioritize open-hand grip.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks Volume cut: 30–40% No new or harder routes in taper',ARRAY['Finger pulley strain (A2 most common)','Rotator cuff impingement','Elbow tendinopathy','Wrist flexor/extensor strain'],ARRAY['Jumping grades without base','No antagonist training','Climbing through finger pain','Wrist extension under load'],'1. Wrist extensor stretching (antagonist — post every session) 2. Sleep (70% of GH secretion during deep sleep — tendon repair) 3. Local finger ice (10 min, 10–15°C) 4. Collagen + Vit C pre-session',ARRAY['Wrist extensor stretching (antagonist — post every session) 2. Sleep (70% of GH secretion during deep sleep — tendon repair) 3. Local finger ice (10 min, 10–15°C) 4. Collagen + Vit C pre-session'],'Finger tendon adaptation lag: Strong mechanistic Climbing injury: Moderate (climbing-specific sports med)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-013','Abseiling','Technical-dominant',NULL,'1–2 supervised sessions with qualified instructor. Technique can be learned in one session; panic management takes 2–3 sessions.',NULL,NULL,'TECHNIQUE ACQUISITION: 2–4 sessions total Skill maintenance: 1 session per 4–6 weeks after technique is solid Physical prep: embedded in climbing training (grip, shoulder endurance)','Not volume-based — technique acquisition. 1–2 sessions per training block.','No separate age adjustment. Same grip/shoulder considerations as climbing.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1 session pre-race if no recent practice.',ARRAY['Rope burns (brake hand)','Shoulder strain','Ankle/shin impact (feet slip on wall)','Back strain (pack weight shift)'],ARRAY['No supervised practice session','No gloves (rope burn at speed)','Pack interfering with device'],'Grip endurance work (dead hangs) is the primary physical prep. Post-session: shoulder and forearm recovery same as climbing.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'Abseiling technique: Practitioner consensus (climbing instruction standards) Injury data for abseiling: Minimal',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-014','Via Ferrata','Technical-dominant',NULL,'3–4 sessions on via ferrata with increasing exposure and difficulty. Physical base: same as climbing — 8–12 wks grip and pull prep.',NULL,NULL,'TECHNIQUE ACQUISITION: 2–4 guided sessions Skill maintenance: 1 session per 4–6 weeks Physical prep: pull-ups, dead hangs, lock-off holds — embedded in climbing training','Not volume-based — technique and exposure acquisition. Y-lanyard clip-in/out must be automatic before race.','Same grip/shoulder considerations as climbing by age.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1 session pre-race to confirm technique and lanyard familiarity.',ARRAY['Finger pulley strain','Shoulder fatigue/strain','Grip failure (serious fall risk)','Psychological: exposure-induced freeze'],ARRAY['No prior via ferrata experience','Insufficient pull-up capacity','Not practicing Y-lanyard in advance'],'Same as climbing: wrist extensor stretch, sleep, collagen + Vit C.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'Via ferrata injury: Limited — climbing literature extrapolated Y-lanyard safety: Strong (UIAA standards)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-017','Snowshoeing','Pure endurance',NULL,'2–3 snowshoe sessions to adapt gait. Physical prep from hiking transfers directly.',NULL,NULL,'BASE: 2–3 easy snowshoe sessions (flat terrain, gait adaptation) BUILD: Progressive terrain + pack weight PEAK: Race-sim conditions + cold-weather practice','Not high-volume — technique and gait adaptation. 2–3 sessions per training block.','No separate age adjustment. Hip abductor fatigue increases with age in wide-gait snowshoe movement — add lateral hip strengthening.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 sessions pre-race if recent snowshoe practice lacking.',ARRAY['Hip flexor strain (abnormal gait)','Lateral hip fatigue / ITBS','Ankle fatigue','Hypothermia','Blisters (boot-binding interaction)'],ARRAY['First snowshoe experience on race day','No cold-weather hiking base','Poor binding fit'],'Same as loaded hiking: leg elevation, CWI, carb resynthesis.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'Snowshoeing physiology: Limited — military + hiking literature extrapolated',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-018','Mountaineering','Mixed',NULL,'1–2 guided glacier days with certified mountain guide. Not self-teachable for safety reasons. Physical base: high aerobic fitness + cold-weather hiking.',NULL,NULL,'TECHNIQUE ACQUISITION: Guided sessions only Physical prep: embedded in hiking volume + strength Crampon + ice axe: guided practice before any independent travel','Not volume-based — guided technique acquisition. Physical fitness transfers from hiking and aerobic base.','No separate age adjustment. High aerobic fitness is the primary physical requirement.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1 guided session pre-race if not recent glacier experience.',ARRAY['Crevasse fall','Ankle torsion (crampon tips catching)','Hypothermia','Frostbite','Falls on steep snow'],ARRAY['No guided training before glacier travel','Unroped on glaciated terrain','Crampon attached incorrectly'],'Cold-weather recovery: warm shower, warm liquids, dry insulation layers before any other modality.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'Mountaineering safety: Strong (UIAA, IFMGA standards) AR-specific mountaineering: Minimal',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-019','Paddle Rafting','Mixed',NULL,'1–2 guided raft trips on moving water before race. River kayak/packraft base provides adequate physical foundation.',NULL,NULL,'TECHNIQUE ACQUISITION: 1–2 guided sessions Physical prep: same shoulder/core work as kayaking Team coordination: paddle command drill with race teammates','Not volume-based — technique acquisition. Physical fitness transfers from kayaking/packrafting.','Same shoulder considerations as kayaking by age.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1 guided session pre-race.',ARRAY['Shoulder strain (fast current)','Back strain (bracing in high-volume water)','Hypothermia','Drowning (Class III+ without skills)'],ARRAY['Class III+ without guided introduction','No PFD','Team with no prior raft experience'],'Same as kayaking: wrist/shoulder stretch, warm liquids post cold-water exposure.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'Rafting safety: Strong (commercial rafting safety standards) AR-specific rafting data: Minimal',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-007','Time-Trial Cycling','Pure endurance',NULL,'NOT a separate discipline — same aerobic and muscular demands as D-006 road cycling. The TT/tri bike is an equipment variant that changes position, injury profile, and requires adaptation time.  TT BIKE: Designed for 20–60 min time trial efforts. Stiff, aggressive, minimal storage. Not designed for self-supported long riding. TRI BIKE: Similar geometry to TT but designed for 90–180 km unsupported efforts with nutrition storage. More stable than TT in race conditions. ROAD BIKE with clip-on aerobars: A compromise — useful for athletes building toward tri bike; lower cost; retains road handling.',NULL,NULL,'POSITION DIFFERENCES vs. ROAD BIKE: • Saddle positioned further forward (opens hip angle for run-off) • Upper body lower — elbows on pads, forearms horizontal • Head raised relative to torso to see road — cervical spine extension under sustained load • Hip angle at saddle: ~50° for Ironman, ~45° for shorter events (BikeDynamics)  ADAPTATION PROTOCOL: • Week 1–2: 20–30 min rides in aero — neck and shoulder soreness is normal and expected • Week 3–4: Build to 60–90 min sustained aero • Weeks 5–8: Full training ride durations in aero • NEVER: Jump to 3+ hr aero ride without progressive adaptation — neck/lower back injury very likely • Run-off effect: Correct saddle fore/aft position on tri bike specifically improves run economy post-bike (2026 study, European J Applied Physiology: 4.7% improvement with dialed fit)','Same ACWR framework as D-006. Additionally: AERO ADAPTATION: Limit hard aero-position efforts in Base phase — build position tolerance before intensity. FIRST SEASON ON TT/TRI BIKE: Reduce ride intensity by 10–15% until position is comfortable; form breakdown under fatigue in aero = injury.','Same as D-006 by age group. Additional consideration: Hamstring and hip flexor flexibility decreases with age — aggressive aero position requires greater flexibility. Masters athletes should prioritize hip flexor and hamstring mobility before adopting aggressive aero position.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Same as D-006: 1–2 weeks, volume cut 40–50%. Do NOT change bike fit or position in taper. Any changes to aero setup must happen ≥4 weeks before race.',ARRAY['Cervical spine strain / neck pain (head raised position in aero — most reported complaint)
Lower back strain (flat-back aero position requires hamstring flexibility)
Hip flexor compression (forward seat)
Knee pain (forward seat changes cleat load — refit required after switching from road to tri bike)
Saddle sores (aero seat position often requires different saddle shape)
Numbness (perineal / sit bones — aero position concentrates pressure differently)'],ARRAY['Immediate full-length aero ride without adaptation','Bike fit NOT updated when switching from road to tri bike (different fit needed — not the same as road bike fit)','Aggressive position before hamstring/hip flexor flexibility is adequate','Wearing time trial helmet that restricts head movement before neck strength is conditioned'],'NECK MANAGEMENT (aero-specific): 1. Neck stretches post every aero ride (flexion, extension, lateral rotation — 30s each hold) 2. Neck strengthening: chin tucks, neck isometrics — pre-season, 3×/week 3. Thoracic extension over foam roller (counteracts sustained flexion) 4. Hip flexor stretch — aero position compresses hip angle more than road bike  All other recovery same as D-006.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'Aero position → neck/lower back: Strong practitioner consensus; Triathlete.com, BikeDynamics fitting data Saddle fore/aft → run economy: Moderate — 2026 study (European J Applied Physiology) Adaptation protocol: Practitioner consensus (fitting literature) Hip angle targets: Moderate (BikeDynamics, fitting practitioner data)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-021','Uphill Skinning','Pure endurance',NULL,'4–6 weeks general aerobic base before on-snow skinning volume. OFF-SNOW: trail running, uphill hiking with poles, stair climbing, and weighted uphill walks provide direct aerobic transfer. Athletes without consistent snow access can build full skimo aerobic fitness off-snow through dry-land training.  ON-SNOW prerequisite: Basic skinning technique (kick turn, flat traversal, skin application) before structured volume training.',4,6,'OFF-SNOW BASE (spring/summer/fall): 6–12 wks • Trail running + uphill hiking with poles as primary modalities • Weighted uphill hikes (simulate pack weight of mandatory kit) • Incline treadmill / stair machine for terrain-specific load • VO2max capacity maintained or built — this transfers directly to skinning aerobic capacity  PRE-SEASON / ON-SNOW INTRO (early winter): 4–6 wks • Gentle skinning sessions (build familiarity with gear + snow conditions) • Kick turns, skin application/removal, descent confidence • Volume: start at 2–3 sessions/week, 1–2 hrs each  BUILD (mid-winter): 6–8 wks • Uphill interval sessions (threshold skinning efforts) • Vertical gain target per week builds progressively • Race-specific circuits (skin + bootpack + descent loops)  PEAK / RACE SEASON: 4–6 wks • Race simulation sessions • Taper 1–2 wks before target event  Full cycle (dry-land to race): 20–26 weeks','10% weekly increase in vertical gain (metres/week) is the primary load metric for skimo — not hours or distance.  RESEARCH: Higher training volume (sessions/week) associated with increased injury risk (PMC9782121). Don''t increase frequency AND vertical gain in same week.  ACWR 0.8–1.3 in vertical gain is the preferred monitoring framework.','40–44: Standard ramp applies if prior ski fitness history. 45–54: 8% weekly gain increase max. Recovery between uphill sessions: 48 hrs minimum. Knee monitoring critical — most common injury site (29.6%, PMC9782121). 55+: 6% weekly gain max. Prioritize dry-land running and hiking volume over rapid on-snow loading. Reduce descent intensity (see D-022).',NULL,8.0,6.0,'2 weeks Vertical gain cut: 40–50% Maintain 2 uphill sessions/week (shorter, maintain aerobic neuromuscular pattern)',ARRAY['Hip flexor strain (repetitive stepping motion on steep skins)','Knee overuse (patellofemoral, IT band — most common skimo injury site at 29.6%, PMC9782121)','Achilles tendinopathy (ski boot restriction alters Achilles loading)','Lower back fatigue (forward lean position + pole loading)','Plantar fascia (boot pressure, especially new or ill-fitting boots)'],ARRAY['Rapid vertical gain increase early in season','Not warming up adequately in cold conditions (muscle/tendon injury risk increases sharply below 0°C)','New boots without adequate break-in','Insufficient core training (non-injured skimo athletes had more core sessions per week, p=0.029)','Jumping to high-angle terrain before aerobic base established'],'1. Core training (primary prevention tool — statistically significant protective effect) 2. Sleep 3. Hip flexor stretch + quad foam roll post-uphill sessions 4. Knee monitoring: any sharp lateral or patellar pain = stop and assess 5. Boot fit: address hot spots early; don''t tolerate pressure points',ARRAY['Core training (primary prevention tool — statistically significant protective effect) 2. Sleep 3. Hip flexor stretch + quad foam roll post-uphill sessions 4. Knee monitoring: any sharp lateral or patellar pain = stop and assess 5. Boot fit: address hot spots early; don''t tolerate pressure points'],'Skimo injury research: Moderate — PMC9782121 (cross-sectional survey, European skimo athletes) Core training protective effect: Moderate (p=0.029 in skimo-specific study; supported by broader winter sports injury prevention literature) Vertical gain as primary load metric: Practitioner consensus (Uphill Athlete methodology, USA Skimo coaching standards) Aerobic transfer from dry-land: Moderate (XC skiing physiology literature; uphill hiking and running as VO2max builders well-established)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-022','Alpine Descent','Technical-dominant',NULL,'EXISTING SKIING BACKGROUND: Athletes with alpine ski history need only adapt to lighter skimo equipment (narrower, less stable, less control) and race-specific descent patterns (gates, variable snow).  NO SKIING BACKGROUND: Alpine ski lessons required before any skimo racing. Minimum 10–15 days on-snow experience before attempting race-format descents on narrow skimo skis.  SKIMO-SPECIFIC DESCENT PREP: Technical courses and gate training once aerobic base is established.',NULL,NULL,'FUNDAMENTAL SKILL (must precede structured skimo training): • Alpine ski proficiency on intermediate terrain = minimum entry  SKIMO-SPECIFIC BUILD: • Sessions on skimo equipment at reduced pace before race-intensity descents • Gate training for sprint/individual format familiarity • Descent on variable snow conditions (firm, tracked, off-piste) • Skin-removal transition into descent: practiced until under 15 seconds • Race-format descents integrated in peak phase','Not volume-based — skill and repetition based. Add one new descent skill element per 2-week block: • Block 1: basic skimo ski control on packed snow • Block 2: gate navigation • Block 3: variable snow (tracked, soft, hard) • Block 4: race-pace descent with transition  Increasing descent speed too quickly is the primary injury mechanism (65.6% of skimo injuries occur on descent — PMC9782121).','45+: Reduce race-intensity descent speed targets. Age-related reduction in reaction time and balance increases fall risk on technical descents. Prioritize technique over speed. 55+: Limit descent intensity to 70–80% of race pace in training. Protective equipment (back protector, knee pads) strongly encouraged at this age group.',NULL,NULL,70.0,'1–2 weeks: maintain 1–2 easy descent sessions (technique focus, reduced speed). No race-intensity descents in taper.',ARRAY['ACL tear (falls on descent — most severe skimo injury)','Knee ligament sprains','Shoulder dislocation/fracture (falls)','Head injury (helmet mandatory — always)','Wrist fracture (pole planting falls)','Hip contusion (impact with snow)

NOTE: 65.6% of all skimo injuries occur during descent (PMC9782121). Impact injuries dominate (68.8% of all injuries), not overuse.'],ARRAY['Racing descent on unfamiliar snow conditions','Attempting gate course without prior practice','Excessive speed before technique is solid','Worn or degraded skimo edges','Not wearing helmet'],'1. Impact injuries (primary risk) — prevention is protective equipment + technique, not recovery modalities 2. Quad and knee recovery: CWI lower body (11–15°C, 10–15 min) after technical descent days 3. Sleep (reaction time and balance are degraded by sleep deprivation — critical for descent safety) 4. Hip flexor + quad stretch post-descent sessions',ARRAY['Impact injuries (primary risk) — prevention is protective equipment + technique, not recovery modalities 2. Quad and knee recovery: CWI lower body (11–15°C, 10–15 min) after technical descent days 3. Sleep (reaction time and balance are degraded by sleep deprivation — critical for descent safety) 4. Hip flexor + quad stretch post-descent sessions'],'Descent injury dominance (65.6%): Strong — PMC9782121 Impact injury predominance (68.8%): Strong — PMC9782121 Equipment weight trade-off (less control for lighter setup): Strong practitioner consensus and biomechanical logic Protective equipment for masters: Practitioner consensus',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-024','Mountain Running','Pure endurance',NULL,'6-8 weeks flat aerobic base (D-001 Trail Running) before introducing steep uphill volume. Athletes need established aerobic engine before extreme vertical hip flexor, calf, and cardiovascular stress.  POLE USE: Legal in most mountain running events (check specific race rules). Pole technique is trainable - practice from Week 1 if poles will be used in races.',6,8,'BASE: 6-8 wks - Standard trail running (D-001) as aerobic engine - Hill repeats: 4-8 x 3-5 min steep at RPE 7-7.5 - Pole technique on uphills if race-relevant - Vertical gain target: 500-1000m/week  BUILD: 6-10 wks - Muscular endurance phase (key before race-specific uphill work) - Long sustained climbs at threshold (60-90 min at RPE 6.5-7) - Power hiking integration: above ~25% grade, power hiking is often faster than running - train it - Vertical: 1500-3000m/week  PEAK: 4-6 wks - Race-specific circuits matching target event vertical gain - VK athletes: near-maximal threshold on steep course (near VO2max throughout, PMC11586947) - Skyrace athletes: sustained effort with combined uphill/downhill sessions - Altitude sessions if racing above 3000m  TAPER: 2-3 wks','PRIMARY METRIC: Vertical gain per week (metres) - same as D-021 Skimo. Distance and time are secondary.  10% weekly increase in vertical gain (heuristic). ACWR 0.8-1.3 in combined vertical load.  Do NOT increase vertical gain AND run frequency in the same week - hip flexor overload is the primary failure mode when both spike.','40-44: Standard ramp; monitor hip flexors and calves. 45-54: Max 8%/week vertical gain increase. Recovery between steep sessions: 48-72 hrs. Calf and Achilles monitoring especially important. 55+: Max 6%/week vertical gain. Alternate steep uphill days with flat recovery runs. Power hiking can replace steep running on recovery days.',NULL,8.0,6.0,'2-3 weeks Vertical cut: 40-50% Maintain 2 uphill sessions/week (shorter, lower grade) Altitude races: arrive >=2 weeks before OR <=3 days before - avoid the acclimatization window of days 3-10',ARRAY['Hip flexor strain (repetitive high knee drive on steep grades) - Calf/Achilles tendinopathy (extreme plantar flexion on steep uphill) - Patellar tendinopathy (uphill knee loading) - Stress reactions (cumulative bone load from extreme vertical) - Altitude sickness (above 2500m: nausea, headache, ataxia = descend immediately)'],ARRAY['Increasing vertical gain too quickly without aerobic base - Neglecting pole technique (poles reduce cardiac drift ~7-10% on long climbs) - Running steep grades that should be power hiked (higher energy cost than hiking above ~25% grade) - Altitude-naive racing without acclimatization - Skipping muscular endurance phase before peak uphill work'],'1. Sleep 2. Hip flexor stretch (mandatory post every steep uphill session) 3. Eccentric calf drop 2x15 post-session 4. CWI lower body (11-15C, 10-15 min) after high-volume vertical days 5. Leg elevation (venous return after prolonged uphill effort)',ARRAY['Sleep 2. Hip flexor stretch (mandatory post every steep uphill session) 3. Eccentric calf drop 2x15 post-session 4. CWI lower body (11-15C, 10-15 min) after high-volume vertical days 5. Leg elevation (venous return after prolonged uphill effort)'],'VK physiology near VO2max throughout: Strong - PMC11586947 (portable gas analyzer study) Power hiking efficiency above 25% grade: Moderate-Strong (trail running coaching consensus + biomechanics) Pole use reducing cardiac drift: Moderate (trekking pole efficiency studies) Vertical gain as primary metric: Practitioner consensus (WMRA, ISF, Uphill Athlete methodology)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-027','Obstacle Course Racing','Mixed',NULL,'VERY LIMITED EVIDENCE: OCR replaces equestrian at senior level from 2025. Junior World Championships have used it since 2023. This entry is based on practitioner consensus, ninja training principles, and the UIPM course specifications - not peer-reviewed sport science.  PHYSICAL PREREQUISITES: - Pull-up minimum: athletes should complete 8+ strict pull-ups before structured OCR training - Grip strength base: 6+ weeks of grip/forearm conditioning before heavy monkey-bar work - Full-body coordination and spatial awareness: body movement patterns on varied apparatus',NULL,NULL,'BASE: 6-8 wks - Upper body pulling strength: pull-ups, lat pulldowns, rows - Grip endurance: hang time, dead hangs, grip trainer - Body weight movement: dips, push-ups, ring rows - Coordination: basic gymnastics-adjacent movements (bar transitions, balance)  BUILD: 4-8 wks (ideally on actual or similar apparatus) - OCR-specific skill sessions: monkey bars, balance beams, tilting ladders, swinging elements - Sprint conditioning: 70m course is a sprint effort, not an endurance effort - train explosive start and full-speed completion - ''Failure protocol'': what to do when you fall/fail an obstacle (get up fast, don''t hesitate)  PEAK: 2-4 wks - Full course simulation: 70m with all 8 obstacles at race pace - Mental practice: course randomization (2 obstacles change per stage) - train adaptability  TAPER: 1 week. Reduce grip-intensive work. Maintain 1 course simulation.','Not volume-based in traditional sense - skill acquisition and strength-to-body-weight ratio drive performance.  GRIP/FOREARM LOADING: Same rules as D-012 (climbing) - max 2 hard grip sessions/week regardless of fitness. Tendons lag muscle by 4-8 weeks.  SPRINT CONDITIONING: 70m course takes approx 20-40 seconds for competitive athletes. Train explosive 20-40 second all-out efforts (similar to short-track sprint conditioning).','45+: Grip and forearm tendon recovery extends. Max 2 hard OCR/grip sessions/week. Reduce falling risk: balance beam and swinging elements require proprioception that decreases with age. 55+: 1 hard OCR session/week. Focus on grip and upper body maintenance. Reduce high-fall-risk apparatus (swinging elements) in training frequency.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1 week Maintain 1 course simulation at moderate pace (technique, not sprint) Avoid heavy grip work in final week - finger and forearm tendons need to arrive fresh',ARRAY['Finger/forearm tendinopathy (grip-intensive obstacles - same mechanism as D-012 climbing)
Shoulder impingement (monkey bars, overhead transitions)
Ankle/knee (falls from obstacles - landing on apparatus or mat)
Lateral epicondylitis (repeated grip loading)
Abrasions/impact injuries (falls on course - expected and minor)

NOTE: Most OCR injuries at competitive level are impact/fall-related (similar to skimo descent pattern), not overuse. Safety mats and controlled surfaces at UIPM events mitigate serious fall risk vs. natural-terrain OCR.'],ARRAY['Attempting monkey bars or advanced apparatus without pull-up base
Not practicing ''failure and recovery'' protocol - stopping at failed obstacle costs more time than efficient skip/reattempt decision
Random obstacle rotation (2 change per stage): not training course adaptability
Grip-intensive OCR training on same day as heavy fencing (grip overlap - forearm fatigue compounds)'],'GRIP/FOREARM: same as D-012 climbing - wrist extensor stretch, local CWI (10 min, 11-15C), collagen + Vit C pre-session SHOULDER: cross-body stretch, rotator cuff external rotation work Sleep: primary recovery BODY WEIGHT: OCR performance is highly sensitive to body weight - heavier athletes have significantly harder time with bodyweight-relative obstacles. Do not over-restrict calories attempting to lose weight rapidly.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'OCR in Modern Pentathlon: Minimal - senior level only from 2025. Junior World Championships data exists but not published in peer-reviewed literature at time of building. Ninja obstacle physiology: Limited - primarily from ninja athlete community and TV production research Grip/forearm tendon training: Strong - extrapolated from D-012 climbing literature (same mechanism) Body weight and OCR performance: Strong practitioner consensus in ninja/OCR coaching community',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-028','Cross-Country Skiing','Pure endurance',NULL,'Two techniques must be treated as distinct sub-disciplines: CLASSIC: diagonal stride, double pole (DP) on flat, herringbone uphill. Requires grip wax or grip zone on ski. SKATE: V1, V2, V2-alternate. Higher power output, faster on groomed snow. Biathlon uses skate technique exclusively in IBU competition.  OFF-SNOW BASE (May-Nov): Roller skiing is the most sport-specific substitute. Classic roller skis for diagonal stride; skate roller skis for V1/V2. Running and cycling provide aerobic base. Double-pole erg (ski erg) for upper body. Roller skiing on pavement has different tibialis anterior loading than snow - introduce gradually.  WORLD-CLASS VOLUME: 861 +/- 90 hrs/year (PMC7947281). Not a realistic target for recreational athletes but establishes the sport''s demands.',NULL,NULL,'GENERAL PREP (May-Aug): Running, cycling, roller skiing, strength. Aerobic base. SPECIFIC PREP (Sept-Nov): Roller skiing dominant. Technique sessions. Strength peaks. COMPETITION (Dec-Apr): On-snow. Technique sessions, intervals, long distance.  INTENSITY DISTRIBUTION: Pyramidal - 88.7% LIT / 6.4% MIT / 4.8% HIT (PMC7947281, world-class data).  DAY-TO-DAY RULE: Never combine elevated volume AND elevated intensity in same day. Only 5% of world-class training days do both (PMC12094961). Alternate: high-volume day -> intensity day -> recovery day, every 3-4 days.','World-class: 861 hrs/year. Recreational competitive: 400-600 hrs/year. ACWR 0.8-1.3. Week-to-week ramp: <=10% in endurance hours.','45-54: Same pyramidal distribution; reduce total hours. Classic technique gentler on joints than skate. 55+: Emphasize classic (lower joint stress). Max 1-2 high-intensity sessions/week.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2-3 weeks. Volume cut 40-50%. Maintain 2 quality sessions/week at race intensity.',ARRAY['Upper body overuse (shoulder/rotator cuff from bilateral pole planting) - Knee (skate technique lateral forces - medial compartment) - Low back (forward-lean in skate) - Shin splints (roller skiing on pavement - tibialis anterior overload) - Hypothermia/frostbite (cold environment, sweating then stopping) - Falls (groomed trail edges, downhill technique)'],ARRAY['Rapid roller skiing introduction on pavement (tibialis anterior overload) - Skipping strength phases - Combining hard intensity and high volume in same session (only 5% of world-class days do this)'],'Sleep (primary for athletes at this volume) - Sauna (traditional Scandinavian XC recovery - heat exposure post-training) - CWI where tolerated - Hip flexor and thoracic rotation mobility',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'World-class training characteristics: Strong - PMC7947281 (world-class long-distance XC skiers) and PMC5741652 (world-class female XC skier) Day-to-day periodization: Strong - PMC12094961 Biathlon vs. XC volume comparison: Moderate - PubMed 37917966 (FENDURA project)',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-030','Gravel Cycling','Pure endurance',NULL,'Same as Road Cycling (D-006): 2–3 weeks Zone 2 before structured intervals. Add loose-surface bike handling at low tire pressure.',2,3,'Same structure as Road Cycling (D-006). Gravel-specific: sustained tempo on mixed surface; loose-surface handling and longer unsupported efforts in Build.','Same as Road Cycling (D-006): 10–15%/week ride hours; FTP intervals +1 rep or +5% duration per 2-week block, not both.','Same as Road Cycling (D-006) by age group; watch patellar tendon.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks. Volume cut 40–50%. Maintain 2 shorter intensity sessions.',ARRAY['Knee pain (patellar tendon, IT band)','Lower back (aero position)','Hand/wrist fatigue from sustained surface vibration'],ARRAY['Rapid intensity escalation without aerobic base','Poor saddle height','Poor cleat alignment'],'Same as Road Cycling (D-006): active recovery spin, hip flexor stretch, sleep.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'Gravel-specific: extrapolated from road cycling literature (Strong for the shared road-cycling claims).',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-031','Cross Country Cycling','Mixed',NULL,'Same as Mountain Biking (D-008): 4–6 weeks road/easy-trail aerobic base and pedaling mechanics before technical XC riding.',4,6,'Same structure as Mountain Biking (D-008), XC-racing focus: aerobic base + sustained climbing power; less technical-descent emphasis than Enduro.','Same as Mountain Biking (D-008): 10–15%/week ride hours; add one new technical element per 2-week block (not by volume).','Same as Mountain Biking (D-008) by age group; CNS-fatigue caps on hard technical days.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks. Volume cut 35–50%. Maintain 1 technical skills session.',ARRAY['Lower back pain','Knee pain (fit)','Hand/wrist numbness','Shoulder impingement','Crashes'],ARRAY['Skipping road base phase','Riding technically while fatigued','Poor bike fit','Insufficient core strength'],'Same as Mountain Biking (D-008): thoracic/lat foam roll, sleep, hip flexor stretch.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'XC-specific: shares Mountain Biking evidence base (practitioner consensus for skill/CNS).',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('D-032','Stand-up Paddleboard','Pure endurance',NULL,'Same as Kayaking (D-010): 4–6 weeks flat-water paddle technique base. SUP-specific: build standing balance and anti-rotation core before volume.',4,6,'Same structure as Kayaking (D-010): BASE flat-water technique + balance; BUILD volume; PEAK race-sim. Standing balance and core stability are the SUP-specific demand.','Same as Kayaking (D-010): 10–15%/week paddle hours; grip sessions max 3×/week.','Same as Kayaking (D-010) by age group; shoulder recovery 48–72 hr for masters.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'1–2 weeks. Volume cut 40–50%.',ARRAY['Shoulder impingement / rotator cuff','Wrist tendinopathy (paddle grip)','Lower back (standing posture, anti-rotation load)'],ARRAY['Arm-dominant paddling','Rapid volume increase','Neglecting shoulder antagonist work','Insufficient core/balance base'],'Same as Kayaking (D-010): rotator-cuff external rotation, wrist extensor stretch, hip flexor stretch.',ARRAY[]::TEXT[],'SUP-specific: extrapolated from kayak/canoe paddle-sports literature (Moderate).',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz);
