  ('Skimo (Sprint)','D-021','Uphill Skinning','Primary',55.0,65.0,48.0,58.0,45.0,55.0,50.0,62.0,'Sprint skinning is explosive — not sustained aerobic. QUALITY SESSION: 3–6×90-sec max-effort skinning intervals with full recovery (simulates sprint heat effort). PHASE SHIFT: Base = aerobic engine via dry-land running/stair climbing; Build = on-snow intervals introduced; Peak = race-simulation heats. Higher absolute intensity vs. Individual/Team format. Pole technique is race-critical — each sprint heat uses poles for explosive uphill propulsion at near-anaerobic capacity.','included','Sprint skinning is explosive — not sustained aerobic.','QUALITY SESSION: 3–6×90-sec max-effort skinning intervals with full recovery (simulates sprint heat effort). | PHASE SHIFT: Base = aerobic engine via dry-land running/stair climbing; | Build = on-snow intervals introduced; | Peak = race-simulation heats. | Higher absolute intensity vs. | Individual/Team format. | Pole technique is race-critical — each sprint heat uses poles for explosive uphill propulsion at near-anaerobic capacity.','Sprint skinning is explosive — not sustained aerobic. QUALITY SESSION: 3–6×90-sec max-effort skinning intervals with full recovery (simulates sprint heat effort). PHASE SHIFT: Base = aerobic engine via dry-land running/stair climbing; Build = on-snow intervals introduced; Peak = race-simulation heats. Higher absolute intensity vs. Individual/Team format. Pole technique is race-critical — each sprint heat uses poles for explosive uphill propulsion at near-anaerobic capacity.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Sprint)','D-022','Alpine Descent','Primary',8.0,16.0,20.0,28.0,24.0,32.0,15.0,22.0,'GATE COURSE DESCENT: Sprint descent is the most technical and CNS-intensive skimo format. Jumps, bumps, and gate navigation at race pace. INJURY RISK: 65.6% of all skimo injuries occur on descent (PMC9782121) — sprint''s aggressive descent compounds this. TRAINING CAP: Max 2 high-commitment descent sessions/week (CNS recovery). PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT: Always train in race protection (helmet, back protector). SKILL PRIORITY: Gate course practice requires specific setup — can''t replicate on open slope. Access to a sprint course or gate training is mandatory for race prep.','included','GATE COURSE DESCENT: Sprint descent is the most technical and CNS-intensive skimo format.','Jumps, bumps, and gate navigation at race pace. | INJURY RISK: 65.6% of all skimo injuries occur on descent (PMC9782121) — sprint''s aggressive descent compounds this. | TRAINING CAP: Max 2 high-commitment descent sessions/week (CNS recovery). | PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT: Always train in race protection (helmet, back protector). | SKILL PRIORITY: Gate course practice requires specific setup — can''t replicate on open slope. | Access to a sprint course or gate training is mandatory for race prep.','GATE COURSE DESCENT: Sprint descent is the most technical and CNS-intensive skimo format. Jumps, bumps, and gate navigation at race pace. INJURY RISK: 65.6% of all skimo injuries occur on descent (PMC9782121) — sprint''s aggressive descent compounds this. TRAINING CAP: Max 2 high-commitment descent sessions/week (CNS recovery). PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT: Always train in race protection (helmet, back protector). SKILL PRIORITY: Gate course practice requires specific setup — can''t replicate on open slope. Access to a sprint course or gate training is mandatory for race prep.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Sprint)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',15.0,22.0,10.0,16.0,8.0,12.0,4.0,6.0,'HIGHER ALLOCATION than other Skimo formats — Sprint benefits most from power-to-weight ratio improvement. FOCUS: Explosive leg power (plyometrics, loaded step-ups, single-leg box jump). Eccentric quad (sprint descent gate course). Core. Hip flexor and calf conditioning for steep uphill. SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 2 | Taper 1.','included','HIGHER ALLOCATION than other Skimo formats — Sprint benefits most from power-to-weight ratio improvement.','FOCUS: Explosive leg power (plyometrics, loaded step-ups, single-leg box jump). | Eccentric quad (sprint descent gate course). | Core. | Hip flexor and calf conditioning for steep uphill. | SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 2 | Taper 1.','HIGHER ALLOCATION than other Skimo formats — Sprint benefits most from power-to-weight ratio improvement. FOCUS: Explosive leg power (plyometrics, loaded step-ups, single-leg box jump). Eccentric quad (sprint descent gate course). Core. Hip flexor and calf conditioning for steep uphill. SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 2 | Taper 1.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Sprint)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',5.0,8.0,4.0,7.0,3.0,6.0,6.0,10.0,'% rises in Taper. CRITICAL: Hip flexor (explosive uphill stride). Quad/knee eccentric recovery after gate-course training (CWI lower body 10–15 min after descent sessions). Warm-up is non-negotiable in cold — sprint format''s explosive demands in cold muscles = acute injury risk. Thorough warm-up before any timed effort.','included','% rises in Taper.','CRITICAL: Hip flexor (explosive uphill stride). | Quad/knee eccentric recovery after gate-course training (CWI lower body 10–15 min after descent sessions). | Warm-up is non-negotiable in cold — sprint format''s explosive demands in cold muscles = acute injury risk. | Thorough warm-up before any timed effort.','% rises in Taper. CRITICAL: Hip flexor (explosive uphill stride). Quad/knee eccentric recovery after gate-course training (CWI lower body 10–15 min after descent sessions). Warm-up is non-negotiable in cold — sprint format''s explosive demands in cold muscles = acute injury risk. Thorough warm-up before any timed effort.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Sprint)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','—',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 7–10 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 8–12 hrs | PEAK: 9–13 hrs | TAPER: 4–7 hrs  Sprint training is intensity-focused rather than volume-focused. Quality ascent intervals and technical descent sessions matter more than accumulated hours. OFF-SNOW BASE: Stair climbing, trail running with explosive hill repeats, plyometrics. TAPER: More aggressive than Individual/Team — 7–10 days out, reduce descent intensity; maintain short uphill intervals for neuromuscular freshness.','included','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 7–10 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 8–12 hrs | PEAK: 9–13 hrs | TAPER: 4–7 hrs','Sprint training is intensity-focused rather than volume-focused. | Quality ascent intervals and technical descent sessions matter more than accumulated hours. | OFF-SNOW BASE: Stair climbing, trail running with explosive hill repeats, plyometrics. | TAPER: More aggressive than Individual/Team — 7–10 days out, reduce descent intensity; | maintain short uphill intervals for neuromuscular freshness.','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 7–10 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 8–12 hrs | PEAK: 9–13 hrs | TAPER: 4–7 hrs

Sprint training is intensity-focused rather than volume-focused. Quality ascent intervals and technical descent sessions matter more than accumulated hours. OFF-SNOW BASE: Stair climbing, trail running with explosive hill repeats, plyometrics. TAPER: More aggressive than Individual/Team — 7–10 days out, reduce descent intensity; maintain short uphill intervals for neuromuscular freshness.','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Vertical / VK)','D-021','Uphill Skinning','Primary',68.0,78.0,60.0,72.0,62.0,74.0,60.0,72.0,'VK IS PURE AEROBIC UPHILL — the entire race is a sustained VO2max effort (30–45 min near VO2max throughout, analogous to D-024 PMC11586947). TRAINING: High-volume aerobic skinning base, with threshold intervals introduced in Build. KEY SESSION: 3–5×8–12 min at threshold on steep consistent grade. Pole technique is performance-critical — practice double-pole push on moderate sections, single plant on steep. VERTICAL TARGET: Base 2000–3000m/wk | Build 3000–5000m/wk | Peak 4000–6000m/wk. DRY-LAND SUBSTITUTE: Uphill running + stair climbing with poles.','included','VK IS PURE AEROBIC UPHILL — the entire race is a sustained VO2max effort (30–45 min near VO2max throughout, analogous to','TRAINING: High-volume aerobic skinning base, with threshold intervals introduced in Build. | KEY SESSION: 3–5×8–12 min at threshold on steep consistent grade. | Pole technique is performance-critical — practice double-pole push on moderate sections, single plant on steep. | VERTICAL TARGET: Base 2000–3000m/wk | Build 3000–5000m/wk | Peak 4000–6000m/wk. | DRY-LAND SUBSTITUTE: Uphill running + stair climbing with poles.','VK IS PURE AEROBIC UPHILL — the entire race is a sustained VO2max effort (30–45 min near VO2max throughout, analogous to D-024 PMC11586947). TRAINING: High-volume aerobic skinning base, with threshold intervals introduced in Build. KEY SESSION: 3–5×8–12 min at threshold on steep consistent grade. Pole technique is performance-critical — practice double-pole push on moderate sections, single plant on steep. VERTICAL TARGET: Base 2000–3000m/wk | Build 3000–5000m/wk | Peak 4000–6000m/wk. DRY-LAND SUBSTITUTE: Uphill running + stair climbing with poles.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Vertical / VK)','D-022','Alpine Descent','Minor',0.0,3.0,4.0,8.0,3.0,7.0,3.0,6.0,'NO DESCENT IN VK RACE — descent training is purely for safe return from training terrain. Maintain basic ski control and confidence — don''t regress. MINIMAL allocation vs. Sprint and Individual formats. Athletes specializing in VK must still be competent on descent to train safely — do not neglect entirely. 1 easy descent session/week in Build/Peak for skill maintenance.','included','NO DESCENT IN VK RACE — descent training is purely for safe return from training terrain.','Maintain basic ski control and confidence — don''t regress. | MINIMAL allocation vs. | Sprint and Individual formats. | Athletes specializing in VK must still be competent on descent to train safely — do not neglect entirely. | 1 easy descent session/week in Build/Peak for skill maintenance.','NO DESCENT IN VK RACE — descent training is purely for safe return from training terrain. Maintain basic ski control and confidence — don''t regress. MINIMAL allocation vs. Sprint and Individual formats. Athletes specializing in VK must still be competent on descent to train safely — do not neglect entirely. 1 easy descent session/week in Build/Peak for skill maintenance.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Vertical / VK)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',16.0,23.0,12.0,18.0,10.0,14.0,4.0,7.0,'HIGHER ALLOCATION than Individual/Team — pure uphill demands greater muscular endurance from hip flexors, calves, and posterior chain. No descent eccentric demand to manage. FOCUS: Hip flexor strength and endurance (repetitive steep uphill step). Calf and Achilles conditioning (sustained plantar flexion on steep grades). Posterior chain (glute/ham). Core (pole planting rhythm under sustained load). SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','included','HIGHER ALLOCATION than Individual/Team — pure uphill demands greater muscular endurance from hip flexors, calves, and po','No descent eccentric demand to manage. | FOCUS: Hip flexor strength and endurance (repetitive steep uphill step). | Calf and Achilles conditioning (sustained plantar flexion on steep grades). | Posterior chain (glute/ham). | Core (pole planting rhythm under sustained load). | SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','HIGHER ALLOCATION than Individual/Team — pure uphill demands greater muscular endurance from hip flexors, calves, and posterior chain. No descent eccentric demand to manage. FOCUS: Hip flexor strength and endurance (repetitive steep uphill step). Calf and Achilles conditioning (sustained plantar flexion on steep grades). Posterior chain (glute/ham). Core (pole planting rhythm under sustained load). SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Vertical / VK)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',5.0,8.0,4.0,7.0,4.0,7.0,6.0,10.0,'% rises in Taper. CRITICAL: Hip flexor (mandatory post every uphill session — repetitive high-knee drive on steep grades = high hip flexor load). Calf/Achilles stretch (eccentric drop 2×15 post session). Knee monitoring — most common skimo injury site (29.6%, PMC9782121). Core training has a statistically significant protective effect (p=0.029 in skimo-specific study). Sleep is the primary recovery tool at VK training volumes.','included','% rises in Taper.','CRITICAL: Hip flexor (mandatory post every uphill session — repetitive high-knee drive on steep grades = high hip flexor load). | Calf/Achilles stretch (eccentric drop 2×15 post session). | Knee monitoring — most common skimo injury site (29.6%, PMC9782121). | Core training has a statistically significant protective effect (p=0.029 in skimo-specific study). | Sleep is the primary recovery tool at VK training volumes.','% rises in Taper. CRITICAL: Hip flexor (mandatory post every uphill session — repetitive high-knee drive on steep grades = high hip flexor load). Calf/Achilles stretch (eccentric drop 2×15 post session). Knee monitoring — most common skimo injury site (29.6%, PMC9782121). Core training has a statistically significant protective effect (p=0.029 in skimo-specific study). Sleep is the primary recovery tool at VK training volumes.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Vertical / VK)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','—',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 7–11 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 8–12 hrs | PEAK: 9–13 hrs | TAPER: 4–7 hrs  VERTICAL GAIN is the primary training load metric — not hours. Base: 2000–3000m/week | Build: 3000–5000m/week | Peak: 4000–6000m/week | Taper: 1500–2500m/week. OFF-SNOW BASE: Uphill running and hiking with poles are the most specific substitutes. 10% weekly increase in vertical gain is the standard ramp (same as D-021 Discipline Library).','included','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 7–11 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 8–12 hrs | PEAK: 9–13 hrs | TAPER: 4–7 hrs','VERTICAL GAIN is the primary training load metric — not hours. | Base: 2000–3000m/week | Build: 3000–5000m/week | Peak: 4000–6000m/week | Taper: 1500–2500m/week. | OFF-SNOW BASE: Uphill running and hiking with poles are the most specific substitutes. | 10% weekly increase in vertical gain is the standard ramp (same as D-021 Discipline Library).','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 7–11 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 8–12 hrs | PEAK: 9–13 hrs | TAPER: 4–7 hrs

VERTICAL GAIN is the primary training load metric — not hours. Base: 2000–3000m/week | Build: 3000–5000m/week | Peak: 4000–6000m/week | Taper: 1500–2500m/week. OFF-SNOW BASE: Uphill running and hiking with poles are the most specific substitutes. 10% weekly increase in vertical gain is the standard ramp (same as D-021 Discipline Library).','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Individual / Team)','D-021','Uphill Skinning','Primary',62.0,72.0,50.0,62.0,52.0,63.0,52.0,65.0,'Individual (1.5–2 hrs) and Team (3–3.5 hrs in pairs) are the flagship ISMF formats and the standard reference for skimo training plans. MIXED AEROBIC/ANAEROBIC: Multiple circuit laps — aerobic base sustains repeated efforts; lactate threshold and VO2max determine lap pace. OFF-SNOW BASE: Trail running + uphill hiking with poles. ON-SNOW INTRO: Gentle skinning → threshold circuits → race-simulation laps. VERTICAL TARGET: Base 1500–2500m/wk | Build 2500–4000m/wk | Peak 3000–5000m/wk. TEAM FORMAT: Train with race partner — proximity rules (30s ascent / 10s descent) require pace coordination that must be rehearsed.','included','Individual (1.5–2 hrs) and Team (3–3.5 hrs in pairs) are the flagship ISMF formats and the standard reference for skimo','MIXED AEROBIC/ANAEROBIC: Multiple circuit laps — aerobic base sustains repeated efforts; | lactate threshold and VO2max determine lap pace. | OFF-SNOW BASE: Trail running + uphill hiking with poles. | ON-SNOW INTRO: Gentle skinning → threshold circuits → race-simulation laps. | VERTICAL TARGET: Base 1500–2500m/wk | Build 2500–4000m/wk | Peak 3000–5000m/wk. | TEAM FORMAT: Train with race partner — proximity rules (30s ascent / 10s descent) require pace coordination that must be rehearsed.','Individual (1.5–2 hrs) and Team (3–3.5 hrs in pairs) are the flagship ISMF formats and the standard reference for skimo training plans. MIXED AEROBIC/ANAEROBIC: Multiple circuit laps — aerobic base sustains repeated efforts; lactate threshold and VO2max determine lap pace. OFF-SNOW BASE: Trail running + uphill hiking with poles. ON-SNOW INTRO: Gentle skinning → threshold circuits → race-simulation laps. VERTICAL TARGET: Base 1500–2500m/wk | Build 2500–4000m/wk | Peak 3000–5000m/wk. TEAM FORMAT: Train with race partner — proximity rules (30s ascent / 10s descent) require pace coordination that must be rehearsed.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Individual / Team)','D-022','Alpine Descent','Primary',5.0,12.0,18.0,26.0,20.0,28.0,13.0,20.0,'RACE-COMMITTED INTENSITY: Individual and Team descents are aggressive. 65.6% of skimo injuries on descent (PMC9782121) — schedule descent sessions when FRESH. SKILL PROGRESSION: Road → packed snow → variable conditions → race-pace. SKIN REMOVAL TRANSITION: Practiced before every descent — target time: <10 sec novice, <7 sec competitive. Stow skins correctly (sticky side folded in) — penalty for dropping. PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT: Always. TEAM FORMAT: Descent proximity rule (10s) — pace coordination on descent is a distinct trainable skill.','included','RACE-COMMITTED INTENSITY: Individual and Team descents are aggressive.','65.6% of skimo injuries on descent (PMC9782121) — schedule descent sessions when FRESH. | SKILL PROGRESSION: Road → packed snow → variable conditions → race-pace. | SKIN REMOVAL TRANSITION: Practiced before every descent — target time: <10 sec novice, <7 sec competitive. | Stow skins correctly (sticky side folded in) — penalty for dropping. | PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT: Always. | TEAM FORMAT: Descent proximity rule (10s) — pace coordination on descent is a distinct trainable skill.','RACE-COMMITTED INTENSITY: Individual and Team descents are aggressive. 65.6% of skimo injuries on descent (PMC9782121) — schedule descent sessions when FRESH. SKILL PROGRESSION: Road → packed snow → variable conditions → race-pace. SKIN REMOVAL TRANSITION: Practiced before every descent — target time: <10 sec novice, <7 sec competitive. Stow skins correctly (sticky side folded in) — penalty for dropping. PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT: Always. TEAM FORMAT: Descent proximity rule (10s) — pace coordination on descent is a distinct trainable skill.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Individual / Team)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',14.0,20.0,10.0,15.0,8.0,12.0,4.0,6.0,'SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Core (non-injured skimo athletes had significantly more core sessions/week, p=0.029 — PMC9782121). Hip flexor and quad (uphill). Eccentric quad (descent loading). Upper body (pole push). Grip and shoulder (pole plant at race pace on sustained ascent). TEAM FORMAT: Both athletes follow same strength plan — fatigue parity on race day.','included','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','FOCUS: Core (non-injured skimo athletes had significantly more core sessions/week, p=0.029 — PMC9782121). | Hip flexor and quad (uphill). | Eccentric quad (descent loading). | Upper body (pole push). | Grip and shoulder (pole plant at race pace on sustained ascent). | TEAM FORMAT: Both athletes follow same strength plan — fatigue parity on race day.','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Core (non-injured skimo athletes had significantly more core sessions/week, p=0.029 — PMC9782121). Hip flexor and quad (uphill). Eccentric quad (descent loading). Upper body (pole push). Grip and shoulder (pole plant at race pace on sustained ascent). TEAM FORMAT: Both athletes follow same strength plan — fatigue parity on race day.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Individual / Team)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',5.0,8.0,4.0,7.0,3.0,6.0,6.0,10.0,'% rises in Taper. CRITICAL: Hip flexor (post every uphill session). Quad/knee recovery after descent sessions (CWI 10–15 min, 11–15°C). Thoracic mobility (sustained forward lean in skinning position). Achilles (boot restriction alters Achilles loading). Boot fit: address hot spots early in the season — pressure points worsen under fatigue and cold. Sleep is the primary recovery tool.','included','% rises in Taper.','CRITICAL: Hip flexor (post every uphill session). | Quad/knee recovery after descent sessions (CWI 10–15 min, 11–15°C). | Thoracic mobility (sustained forward lean in skinning position). | Achilles (boot restriction alters Achilles loading). | Boot fit: address hot spots early in the season — pressure points worsen under fatigue and cold. | Sleep is the primary recovery tool.','% rises in Taper. CRITICAL: Hip flexor (post every uphill session). Quad/knee recovery after descent sessions (CWI 10–15 min, 11–15°C). Thoracic mobility (sustained forward lean in skinning position). Achilles (boot restriction alters Achilles loading). Boot fit: address hot spots early in the season — pressure points worsen under fatigue and cold. Sleep is the primary recovery tool.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Individual / Team)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','—',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–12 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 9–14 hrs | PEAK: 10–16 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs  Individual format is the standard skimo training reference. TEAM: Add partner coordination sessions (proximity drills, pace-matching) from Build phase. Team racing requires race-partner chemistry — train together, not just individually. SEASONAL STRUCTURE (unique to all skimo): Off-snow (May–Oct): running and hiking primary. Pre-season on-snow (Nov–Dec): technique and gentle volume. Competition season (Jan–Mar): race-simulation and taper. 80/20 applies to skinning — 80% Zone 2 aerobic, 20% threshold.','included','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–12 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 9–14 hrs | PEAK: 10–16 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs','Individual format is the standard skimo training reference. | TEAM: Add partner coordination sessions (proximity drills, pace-matching) from Build phase. | Team racing requires race-partner chemistry — train together, not just individually. | SEASONAL STRUCTURE (unique to all skimo): Off-snow (May–Oct): running and hiking primary. | Pre-season on-snow (Nov–Dec): technique and gentle volume. | Competition season (Jan–Mar): race-simulation and taper. | 80/20 applies to skinning — 80% Zone 2 aerobic, 20% threshold.','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–12 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 9–14 hrs | PEAK: 10–16 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs

Individual format is the standard skimo training reference. TEAM: Add partner coordination sessions (proximity drills, pace-matching) from Build phase. Team racing requires race-partner chemistry — train together, not just individually. SEASONAL STRUCTURE (unique to all skimo): Off-snow (May–Oct): running and hiking primary. Pre-season on-snow (Nov–Dec): technique and gentle volume. Competition season (Jan–Mar): race-simulation and taper. 80/20 applies to skinning — 80% Zone 2 aerobic, 20% threshold.','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Long Distance / Grand Traverse)','D-021','Uphill Skinning','Primary',63.0,73.0,55.0,67.0,57.0,68.0,55.0,68.0,'ULTRA-ENDURANCE FORMAT: 5–12 hrs with multiple major ascents. PRIMARY TRAINING STIMULUS: Back-to-back long skinning days in Peak (e.g., 4–5 hrs Day 1 + 2–3 hrs Day 2) — the specific adaptation no intervals can replace. NIGHT SKINNING: Mandatory for Grand Traverse (departs at night). Practice 1 overnight session in Peak — headlamp technique, cold-weather decision-making, fatigue management. NUTRITION: Train fueling while moving from first long session. Caloric target: 250–350 kcal/hr. VERTICAL TARGET: Base 1500–2500m/wk | Build 2500–4000m/wk | Peak 3500–5500m/wk.','included','ULTRA-ENDURANCE FORMAT: 5–12 hrs with multiple major ascents.','PRIMARY TRAINING STIMULUS: Back-to-back long skinning days in Peak (e.g., 4–5 hrs Day 1 + 2–3 hrs Day 2) — the specific adaptation no intervals can replace. | NIGHT SKINNING: Mandatory for Grand Traverse (departs at night). | Practice 1 overnight session in Peak — headlamp technique, cold-weather decision-making, fatigue management. | NUTRITION: Train fueling while moving from first long session. | Caloric target: 250–350 kcal/hr. | VERTICAL TARGET: Base 1500–2500m/wk | Build 2500–4000m/wk | Peak 3500–5500m/wk.','ULTRA-ENDURANCE FORMAT: 5–12 hrs with multiple major ascents. PRIMARY TRAINING STIMULUS: Back-to-back long skinning days in Peak (e.g., 4–5 hrs Day 1 + 2–3 hrs Day 2) — the specific adaptation no intervals can replace. NIGHT SKINNING: Mandatory for Grand Traverse (departs at night). Practice 1 overnight session in Peak — headlamp technique, cold-weather decision-making, fatigue management. NUTRITION: Train fueling while moving from first long session. Caloric target: 250–350 kcal/hr. VERTICAL TARGET: Base 1500–2500m/wk | Build 2500–4000m/wk | Peak 3500–5500m/wk.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Long Distance / Grand Traverse)','D-022','Alpine Descent','Primary',5.0,12.0,15.0,22.0,18.0,25.0,12.0,20.0,'MULTIPLE LONG DESCENTS at sustained (not sprint) effort. Efficiency matters more than peak speed — a 10-sec crash costs more in 10-hr race than in 3-min sprint. FATIGUE MANAGEMENT: Schedule descent sessions when fresh — tired technical riding/skiing = crash risk. PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT: Always. MULTI-DAY TAPER: Reduce high-commitment descents 14 days before multi-day event (vs. 7 days for single-day races) — CNS-intensive nature of aggressive descents means longer CNS recovery window is needed.','included','MULTIPLE LONG DESCENTS at sustained (not sprint) effort.','Efficiency matters more than peak speed — a 10-sec crash costs more in 10-hr race than in 3-min sprint. | FATIGUE MANAGEMENT: Schedule descent sessions when fresh — tired technical riding/skiing = crash risk. | PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT: Always. | MULTI-DAY TAPER: Reduce high-commitment descents 14 days before multi-day event (vs. | 7 days for single-day races) — CNS-intensive nature of aggressive descents means longer CNS recovery window is needed.','MULTIPLE LONG DESCENTS at sustained (not sprint) effort. Efficiency matters more than peak speed — a 10-sec crash costs more in 10-hr race than in 3-min sprint. FATIGUE MANAGEMENT: Schedule descent sessions when fresh — tired technical riding/skiing = crash risk. PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT: Always. MULTI-DAY TAPER: Reduce high-commitment descents 14 days before multi-day event (vs. 7 days for single-day races) — CNS-intensive nature of aggressive descents means longer CNS recovery window is needed.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Long Distance / Grand Traverse)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',12.0,18.0,8.0,13.0,6.0,10.0,3.0,5.0,'LOWER ALLOCATION than Sprint/VK — long-distance volume leaves less recovery for strength. SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2 | Build 1–2 | Peak 1 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Core durability (not peak strength — endurance under 10+ hr sustained load). Hip flexor and posterior chain. Eccentric quad (long descents). Upper body endurance (pole plant for 10+ hrs). Grip and cold-hand tolerance. NEVER schedule strength the day before a back-to-back long skinning session in peak phase.','included','LOWER ALLOCATION than Sprint/VK — long-distance volume leaves less recovery for strength.','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2 | Build 1–2 | Peak 1 | Taper 1. | FOCUS: Core durability (not peak strength — endurance under 10+ hr sustained load). | Hip flexor and posterior chain. | Eccentric quad (long descents). | Upper body endurance (pole plant for 10+ hrs). | Grip and cold-hand tolerance. | NEVER schedule strength the day before a back-to-back long skinning session in peak phase.','LOWER ALLOCATION than Sprint/VK — long-distance volume leaves less recovery for strength. SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2 | Build 1–2 | Peak 1 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Core durability (not peak strength — endurance under 10+ hr sustained load). Hip flexor and posterior chain. Eccentric quad (long descents). Upper body endurance (pole plant for 10+ hrs). Grip and cold-hand tolerance. NEVER schedule strength the day before a back-to-back long skinning session in peak phase.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Long Distance / Grand Traverse)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',5.0,8.0,4.0,7.0,4.0,7.0,6.0,10.0,'HIGHER BASE ALLOCATION vs. other Skimo formats — back-to-back training days require deliberate recovery. Lower back (sustained forward lean for 8+ hrs — hip flexor + lumbar stretching after every long session). Knee (multi-hour descent load). SLEEP DEPRIVATION RECOVERY: After overnight training session, take a full recovery day. Cognitive performance degrades with sleep deprivation — navigation errors increase sharply. Sleep is the primary cognitive and physical recovery tool for long-distance format.','included','HIGHER BASE ALLOCATION vs.','other Skimo formats — back-to-back training days require deliberate recovery. | Lower back (sustained forward lean for 8+ hrs — hip flexor + lumbar stretching after every long session). | Knee (multi-hour descent load). | SLEEP DEPRIVATION RECOVERY: After overnight training session, take a full recovery day. | Cognitive performance degrades with sleep deprivation — navigation errors increase sharply. | Sleep is the primary cognitive and physical recovery tool for long-distance format.','HIGHER BASE ALLOCATION vs. other Skimo formats — back-to-back training days require deliberate recovery. Lower back (sustained forward lean for 8+ hrs — hip flexor + lumbar stretching after every long session). Knee (multi-hour descent load). SLEEP DEPRIVATION RECOVERY: After overnight training session, take a full recovery day. Cognitive performance degrades with sleep deprivation — navigation errors increase sharply. Sleep is the primary cognitive and physical recovery tool for long-distance format.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Skimo (Long Distance / Grand Traverse)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','—',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–12 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 10–16 hrs | PEAK: 12–20 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs  Back-to-back long days are counted in PEAK total and will be the highest-load training unit — plan the entire week around them. NIGHT SESSION: Include 1 overnight skinning session in peak for events with night segments (Grand Traverse). OFF-SNOW BASE: Ultra-style back-to-back long hikes/runs with poles are the most specific substitute. TAPER: 2–3 weeks. Reduce back-to-back days in final 2 weeks. Final high-commitment descent: 14 days before race (longer CNS taper vs. single-day).','included','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–12 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 10–16 hrs | PEAK: 12–20 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs','Back-to-back long days are counted in PEAK total and will be the highest-load training unit — plan the entire week around them. | NIGHT SESSION: Include 1 overnight skinning session in peak for events with night segments (Grand Traverse). | OFF-SNOW BASE: Ultra-style back-to-back long hikes/runs with poles are the most specific substitute. | TAPER: 2–3 weeks. | Reduce back-to-back days in final 2 weeks. | Final high-commitment descent: 14 days before race (longer CNS taper vs. | single-day).','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–12 hrs (dry-land) | BUILD: 10–16 hrs | PEAK: 12–20 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs

Back-to-back long days are counted in PEAK total and will be the highest-load training unit — plan the entire week around them. NIGHT SESSION: Include 1 overnight skinning session in peak for events with night segments (Grand Traverse). OFF-SNOW BASE: Ultra-style back-to-back long hikes/runs with poles are the most specific substitute. TAPER: 2–3 weeks. Reduce back-to-back days in final 2 weeks. Final high-commitment descent: 14 days before race (longer CNS taper vs. single-day).','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Mountain Running / Skyrunning','D-001','Trail Running','Primary',55.0,65.0,40.0,50.0,35.0,45.0,50.0,60.0,'Standard D-001 fills easy/recovery days and aerobic volume. % drops in Build/Peak as D-024 and D-024 increase. Never below 30%.  SESSIONS/WEEK: Base: 4-5 | Build: 3-4 | Peak: 3-4 | Taper: 3-4  [AUDIT 2026-05-05] STRUCTURAL: Wide phase bands (Peak hi 123% on this sport) reflect ISF sub-format slide between VK / SkyRace / SkyUltra. VK specialists shift Uphill to 35-45% with Trail base dropping to ~35%; SkyRace and SkyUltra athletes use the standard split. Bands span the credible range across all three sub-formats.','included','Standard D-001 fills easy/recovery days and aerobic volume.','% drops in Build/Peak as D-024 and D-024 increase. | Never below 30%. | SESSIONS/WEEK: Base: 4-5 | Build: 3-4 | Peak: 3-4 | Taper: 3-4 | [AUDIT 2026-05-05] STRUCTURAL: Wide phase bands (Peak hi 123% on this sport) reflect ISF sub-format slide between VK / SkyRace / SkyUltra. | VK specialists shift Uphill to 35-45% with Trail base dropping to ~35%; | SkyRace and SkyUltra athletes use the standard split. | Bands span the credible range across all three sub-formats.','Standard D-001 fills easy/recovery days and aerobic volume. % drops in Build/Peak as D-024 and D-024 increase. Never below 30%.

