  ('Fell Running',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',10.0,12.0,7.0,10.0,5.0,8.0,3.0,5.0,'ANKLE AND LOWER LEG EMPHASIS - unique to fell running: - Single-leg calf raises (high volume - 3x20 each leg) - Single-leg balance on unstable surfaces (BOSU, wobble board, uneven ground) - Ankle eversion/inversion resistance (band work) - Step-down eccentric (downhill prep)  CORE: Planks, side planks, anti-rotation - stability on unpredictable terrain. HIP ABDUCTORS: Lateral band walks, side-lying abduction - stability through heather/tussock ground.  [AUDIT 2026-05-05] Q-MF1: Strength % at 10-12 Base sits at parity with Marathon (Mountain). Same duration/intensity profile, different specificity CONTENT. Fell Running emphasizes reactive-stability and ankle/lower-leg work (single-leg calf raises, BOSU/wobble board, eversion/inversion) for unpredictable fell terrain. Marathon (Mountain) emphasizes sustained-climb power and eccentric quad. Same % budget; different programming.','included','ANKLE AND LOWER LEG EMPHASIS - unique to fell running:','- Single-leg calf raises (high volume - 3x20 each leg) | - Single-leg balance on unstable surfaces (BOSU, wobble board, uneven ground) | - Ankle eversion/inversion resistance (band work) | - Step-down eccentric (downhill prep) | CORE: Planks, side planks, anti-rotation - stability on unpredictable terrain. | HIP ABDUCTORS: Lateral band walks, side-lying abduction - stability through heather/tussock ground. | [AUDIT 2026-05-05] Q-MF1: Strength % at 10-12 Base sits at parity with Marathon (Mountain). | Same duration/intensity profile, different specificity CONTENT. | Fell Running emphasizes reactive-stability and ankle/lower-leg work (single-leg calf raises, BOSU/wobble board, eversion/inversion) for unpredictable fell terrain. | Marathon (Mountain) emphasizes sustained-climb power and eccentric quad. | Same % budget; | different programming.','ANKLE AND LOWER LEG EMPHASIS - unique to fell running:
- Single-leg calf raises (high volume - 3x20 each leg)
- Single-leg balance on unstable surfaces (BOSU, wobble board, uneven ground)
- Ankle eversion/inversion resistance (band work)
- Step-down eccentric (downhill prep)

CORE: Planks, side planks, anti-rotation - stability on unpredictable terrain.
HIP ABDUCTORS: Lateral band walks, side-lying abduction - stability through heather/tussock ground.

[AUDIT 2026-05-05] Q-MF1: Strength % at 10-12 Base sits at parity with Marathon (Mountain). Same duration/intensity profile, different specificity CONTENT. Fell Running emphasizes reactive-stability and ankle/lower-leg work (single-leg calf raises, BOSU/wobble board, eversion/inversion) for unpredictable fell terrain. Marathon (Mountain) emphasizes sustained-climb power and eccentric quad. Same % budget; different programming.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Fell Running',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',4.0,6.0,4.0,6.0,4.0,6.0,6.0,9.0,'Hip flexor, calf/Achilles, ankle range; quad mobility for downhill DOMS recovery.  [AUDIT 2026-05-05] Q-MF2: Band 4-6% Base/Build/Peak verified (FRA literature, Spinks coaching practice). Phase shape is FLAT-% (not constant-absolute-time): absolute mobility time grows across phases (4-6% x 8 hr Base = 19-29 min/wk -> 4-6% x 13 hr Peak = 31-47 min/wk). Intentional to provide more terrain-recovery time as volume rises. Content emphasis: ankle range and hip flexor are fell-specific priorities (heather/tussock terrain).','included','Hip flexor, calf/Achilles, ankle range;','quad mobility for downhill DOMS recovery. | [AUDIT 2026-05-05] Q-MF2: Band 4-6% Base/Build/Peak verified (FRA literature, Spinks coaching practice). | Phase shape is FLAT-% (not constant-absolute-time): absolute mobility time grows across phases (4-6% x 8 hr Base = 19-29 min/wk -> 4-6% x 13 hr Peak = 31-47 min/wk). | Intentional to provide more terrain-recovery time as volume rises. | Content emphasis: ankle range and hip flexor are fell-specific priorities (heather/tussock terrain).','Hip flexor, calf/Achilles, ankle range; quad mobility for downhill DOMS recovery.

