  ('Marathon (Road)','D-002','Road Running','Primary',80.0,90.0,82.0,92.0,84.0,94.0,84.0,94.0,'Standard road running periodization. Highest LIT (low-intensity training) ratio of the marathon sub-formats. SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 5-6 (1 long + 1 quality + easy). Build/Peak: 5-6 (1 long + 2 quality + easy). Taper: 4-5. Long run: 18-22 mi peak. Quality: tempo, marathon-pace, VO2 intervals.  [AUDIT 2026-05-05] Q-MF3: ''Highest LIT ratio of the marathon family'' claim verified vs Marathon (Trail), Marathon (Mountain), Mountain Running (~77% per Jornet 2022 data), and Fell Running. Family-scope qualifier is correct as-written. For global cross-sport ranking, see sheet ''Cross-Sport Properties'' entry LIT_RATIO_001 (Ultramarathon (Road) likely sits slightly higher globally; Marathon (Road) is the running-family leader by a small margin).','included','Standard road running periodization.','Highest LIT (low-intensity training) ratio of the marathon sub-formats. | SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 5-6 (1 long + 1 quality + easy). | Build/Peak: 5-6 (1 long + 2 quality + easy). | Taper: 4-5. | Long run: 18-22 mi peak. | Quality: tempo, marathon-pace, VO2 intervals. | [AUDIT 2026-05-05] Q-MF3: ''Highest LIT ratio of the marathon family'' claim verified vs Marathon (Trail), Marathon (Mountain), Mountain Running (~77% per Jornet 2022 data), and Fell Running. | Family-scope qualifier is correct as-written. | For global cross-sport ranking, see sheet ''Cross-Sport Properties'' entry LIT_RATIO_001 (Ultramarathon (Road) likely sits slightly higher globally; | Marathon (Road) is the running-family leader by a small margin).','Standard road running periodization. Highest LIT (low-intensity training) ratio of the marathon sub-formats.
SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 5-6 (1 long + 1 quality + easy). Build/Peak: 5-6 (1 long + 2 quality + easy). Taper: 4-5.
