  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Road / Gran Fondo)','D-006','Road Cycling','Primary',90.0,95.0,90.0,93.0,91.0,93.0,92.0,95.0,'PRIMARY LOAD: Long ride protocol builds ~80% of event duration (or 70% for events >6 hrs). 4–5 sessions/week. FUELING: Nutrition rehearsal mandatory every ride >90 min. Target 60–90g carbs/hr from hour 1. SADDLE ENDURANCE: Specific trainable adaptation — build progressively, don''t jump from 2-hr rides to a 7-hr event. ULTRA-ENDURANCE (RAAM, 500km+): Adds sleep management, back-to-back day training, and mental fatigue management. PACING: Even power output (±3–5% of target watts) consistently outperforms variable pacing for events over 4 hours. Power meter strongly recommended.','included','PRIMARY LOAD: Long ride protocol builds ~80% of event duration (or 70% for events >6 hrs).','4–5 sessions/week. | FUELING: Nutrition rehearsal mandatory every ride >90 min. | Target 60–90g carbs/hr from hour 1. | SADDLE ENDURANCE: Specific trainable adaptation — build progressively, don''t jump from 2-hr rides to a 7-hr event. | ULTRA-ENDURANCE (RAAM, 500km+): Adds sleep management, back-to-back day training, and mental fatigue management. | PACING: Even power output (±3–5% of target watts) consistently outperforms variable pacing for events over 4 hours. | Power meter strongly recommended.','PRIMARY LOAD: Long ride protocol builds ~80% of event duration (or 70% for events >6 hrs). 4–5 sessions/week. FUELING: Nutrition rehearsal mandatory every ride >90 min. Target 60–90g carbs/hr from hour 1. SADDLE ENDURANCE: Specific trainable adaptation — build progressively, don''t jump from 2-hr rides to a 7-hr event. ULTRA-ENDURANCE (RAAM, 500km+): Adds sleep management, back-to-back day training, and mental fatigue management. PACING: Even power output (±3–5% of target watts) consistently outperforms variable pacing for events over 4 hours. Power meter strongly recommended.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Road / Gran Fondo)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',3.0,12.0,4.0,8.0,2.0,6.0,2.0,3.0,'SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Core (anti-extension for long riding position), hip flexor, single-leg power. Wide BASE band (3–12%) reflects that strength takes a back seat to high road cycling volume — lower end of band is expected for athletes at peak weekly hours.','included','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','FOCUS: Core (anti-extension for long riding position), hip flexor, single-leg power. | Wide BASE band (3–12%) reflects that strength takes a back seat to high road cycling volume — lower end of band is expected for athletes at peak weekly hours.','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Core (anti-extension for long riding position), hip flexor, single-leg power. Wide BASE band (3–12%) reflects that strength takes a back seat to high road cycling volume — lower end of band is expected for athletes at peak weekly hours.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Road / Gran Fondo)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',3.0,5.0,3.0,5.0,2.0,5.0,5.0,8.0,'% rises in Taper. CRITICAL: Hip flexor (daily — prolonged cycling tightens hip flexors regardless of position). Lower back (sustained saddle time). Hamstrings. Neck and thoracic (especially if aero bars are used). Post-long-ride: hip flexor stretch before any other recovery modality.','included','% rises in Taper.','CRITICAL: Hip flexor (daily — prolonged cycling tightens hip flexors regardless of position). | Lower back (sustained saddle time). | Hamstrings. | Neck and thoracic (especially if aero bars are used). | Post-long-ride: hip flexor stretch before any other recovery modality.','% rises in Taper. CRITICAL: Hip flexor (daily — prolonged cycling tightens hip flexors regardless of position). Lower back (sustained saddle time). Hamstrings. Neck and thoracic (especially if aero bars are used). Post-long-ride: hip flexor stretch before any other recovery modality.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Road / Gran Fondo)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','-',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–14 hrs | BUILD: 10–18 hrs | PEAK: 12–22 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs  Gran Fondo / Century: 10–16 hrs peak. Ultra-endurance road (RAAM, 500km+): 18–25 hrs peak. Long ride is the week''s anchor — plan all other sessions around recovery from it. 80/20 INTENSITY: 80% Zone 2. Common error: turning every long ride into a tempo effort — this produces fatigue without the aerobic base adaptations that long events require.','included','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–14 hrs | BUILD: 10–18 hrs | PEAK: 12–22 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs','Gran Fondo / Century: 10–16 hrs peak. | Ultra-endurance road (RAAM, 500km+): 18–25 hrs peak. | Long ride is the week''s anchor — plan all other sessions around recovery from it. | 80/20 INTENSITY: 80% Zone 2. | Common error: turning every long ride into a tempo effort — this produces fatigue without the aerobic base adaptations that long events require.','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–14 hrs | BUILD: 10–18 hrs | PEAK: 12–22 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs

Gran Fondo / Century: 10–16 hrs peak. Ultra-endurance road (RAAM, 500km+): 18–25 hrs peak. Long ride is the week''s anchor — plan all other sessions around recovery from it. 80/20 INTENSITY: 80% Zone 2. Common error: turning every long ride into a tempo effort — this produces fatigue without the aerobic base adaptations that long events require.','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Gravel)','D-006','Road Cycling','Primary',83.0,88.0,83.0,88.0,86.0,88.0,88.0,92.0,'GRAVEL ≠ ROAD CYCLING WITH DIRT: 5–15% energy penalty on loose gravel vs. road equivalent pace. Mixed surface transitions (asphalt → gravel → packed dirt) create variable power demands — train with Tempo intervals interspersed in long rides to simulate. SELF-SUPPORTED NUTRITION: Aid stations sparse or absent. Practice carrying and eating from bike every long training ride. ULTRA-GRAVEL (Unbound 200+): Back-to-back training days (5–7 hrs Day 1 + 3–5 hrs Day 2) are the key peak stimulus. Target 70% of event duration in peak long ride.','included','GRAVEL ≠ ROAD CYCLING WITH DIRT: 5–15% energy penalty on loose gravel vs.','road equivalent pace. | Mixed surface transitions (asphalt → gravel → packed dirt) create variable power demands — train with Tempo intervals interspersed in long rides to simulate. | SELF-SUPPORTED NUTRITION: Aid stations sparse or absent. | Practice carrying and eating from bike every long training ride. | ULTRA-GRAVEL (Unbound 200+): Back-to-back training days (5–7 hrs Day 1 + 3–5 hrs Day 2) are the key peak stimulus. | Target 70% of event duration in peak long ride.','GRAVEL ≠ ROAD CYCLING WITH DIRT: 5–15% energy penalty on loose gravel vs. road equivalent pace. Mixed surface transitions (asphalt → gravel → packed dirt) create variable power demands — train with Tempo intervals interspersed in long rides to simulate. SELF-SUPPORTED NUTRITION: Aid stations sparse or absent. Practice carrying and eating from bike every long training ride. ULTRA-GRAVEL (Unbound 200+): Back-to-back training days (5–7 hrs Day 1 + 3–5 hrs Day 2) are the key peak stimulus. Target 70% of event duration in peak long ride.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Gravel)','D-008','Mountain Biking','Secondary',5.0,10.0,5.0,10.0,5.0,10.0,0.0,5.0,'*CONDITIONAL — 10–18% MTB sessions for technical confidence on loose surfaces, off-camber roads, and gravel-specific cornering. Importance scales with course profile and athlete''s existing technical skill. Beginners: prioritize higher end. Experienced technical riders: lower end sufficient.','included','Importance scales with course profile and athlete''s existing technical skill.','*CONDITIONAL — 10–18% MTB sessions for technical confidence on loose surfaces, off-camber roads, and gravel-specific cornering. | Beginners: prioritize higher end. | Experienced technical riders: lower end sufficient.','*CONDITIONAL — 10–18% MTB sessions for technical confidence on loose surfaces, off-camber roads, and gravel-specific cornering. Importance scales with course profile and athlete''s existing technical skill. Beginners: prioritize higher end. Experienced technical riders: lower end sufficient.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Gravel)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',5.0,10.0,4.0,8.0,2.0,6.0,2.0,3.0,'Core + hip flexor + single-leg power (same as road). ADD CNS component: balance and off-camber load from technical riding demands more neuromuscular stability work than pure road format. SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','included','Core + hip flexor + single-leg power (same as road).','ADD CNS component: balance and off-camber load from technical riding demands more neuromuscular stability work than pure road format. | SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','Core + hip flexor + single-leg power (same as road). ADD CNS component: balance and off-camber load from technical riding demands more neuromuscular stability work than pure road format. SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Gravel)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',3.0,5.0,3.0,5.0,2.0,5.0,5.0,8.0,'Same as Road/Gran Fondo. Additional for gravel: thoracic rotation and shoulder stability (gravel vibration and rough surface demands more upper body stabilization than smooth road). Wrist/forearm stretching post-rides on rough gravel surfaces.','included','Same as Road/Gran Fondo.','Additional for gravel: thoracic rotation and shoulder stability (gravel vibration and rough surface demands more upper body stabilization than smooth road). | Wrist/forearm stretching post-rides on rough gravel surfaces.','Same as Road/Gran Fondo. Additional for gravel: thoracic rotation and shoulder stability (gravel vibration and rough surface demands more upper body stabilization than smooth road). Wrist/forearm stretching post-rides on rough gravel surfaces.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Gravel)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','-',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–14 hrs | BUILD: 10–18 hrs | PEAK: 12–22 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs  Ultra-gravel (Unbound 200+): same volume targets as ultra-endurance road. Standard gravel (50–200 miles): 10–16 hrs peak. TECHNICAL HANDLING: MTB allocation can replace some road volume in Build/Peak — do not add MTB on top of full road volume. It substitutes, not adds.','included','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–14 hrs | BUILD: 10–18 hrs | PEAK: 12–22 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs','Ultra-gravel (Unbound 200+): same volume targets as ultra-endurance road. | Standard gravel (50–200 miles): 10–16 hrs peak. | TECHNICAL HANDLING: MTB allocation can replace some road volume in Build/Peak — do not add MTB on top of full road volume. | It substitutes, not adds.','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–14 hrs | BUILD: 10–18 hrs | PEAK: 12–22 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs

Ultra-gravel (Unbound 200+): same volume targets as ultra-endurance road. Standard gravel (50–200 miles): 10–16 hrs peak. TECHNICAL HANDLING: MTB allocation can replace some road volume in Build/Peak — do not add MTB on top of full road volume. It substitutes, not adds.','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Long Distance / Endurance Cycling (Time Trial)','D-006','Road Cycling','Primary',88.0,93.0,87.0,92.0,89.0,92.0,91.0,93.0,'PURE THRESHOLD SPORT: FTP is the primary performance variable. PACING: Even power or very slight negative split. Going out 5% too hard costs more time in the second half than the initial speed gain (PMC5104959). AERO POSITION ENDURANCE: Threshold power in TT position is 3–8% lower than road bike. The aero position must be trained specifically — all threshold intervals in aero. KEY SESSIONS: TT pace intervals: 2×15 min building to 2×25–30 min at 91–105% FTP in aero. FTP TEST: Re-test every 6–8 weeks — TT is entirely FTP-dependent.','included','PURE THRESHOLD SPORT: FTP is the primary performance variable.','PACING: Even power or very slight negative split. | Going out 5% too hard costs more time in the second half than the initial speed gain (PMC5104959). | AERO POSITION ENDURANCE: Threshold power in TT position is 3–8% lower than road bike. | The aero position must be trained specifically — all threshold intervals in aero. | KEY SESSIONS: TT pace intervals: 2×15 min building to 2×25–30 min at 91–105% FTP in aero. | FTP TEST: Re-test every 6–8 weeks — TT is entirely FTP-dependent.','PURE THRESHOLD SPORT: FTP is the primary performance variable. PACING: Even power or very slight negative split. Going out 5% too hard costs more time in the second half than the initial speed gain (PMC5104959). AERO POSITION ENDURANCE: Threshold power in TT position is 3–8% lower than road bike. The aero position must be trained specifically — all threshold intervals in aero. KEY SESSIONS: TT pace intervals: 2×15 min building to 2×25–30 min at 91–105% FTP in aero. FTP TEST: Re-test every 6–8 weeks — TT is entirely FTP-dependent.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
