  ('Cross-Country / Nordic Skiing',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',4.0,7.0,3.0,6.0,2.0,5.0,5.0,9.0,'% rises in Taper as total volume drops; absolute time similar throughout. CRITICAL AREAS: Hip flexor (skate technique sustained lateral push). Thoracic rotation (bilateral pole plant requires full thoracic mobility — skiers who restrict rotation lose power at every cycle). Shoulder posterior capsule (high bilateral pole volume). WARM-UP NON-NEGOTIABLE: Cold-weather muscles require 10–15 min warm-up before any intensity — cold tendon injury risk is significantly elevated. Sauna recovery (traditional Scandinavian XC practice) has meaningful evidence for reducing DOMS and improving recovery between high-volume sessions.','included','% rises in Taper as total volume drops;','absolute time similar throughout. | CRITICAL AREAS: Hip flexor (skate technique sustained lateral push). | Thoracic rotation (bilateral pole plant requires full thoracic mobility — skiers who restrict rotation lose power at every cycle). | Shoulder posterior capsule (high bilateral pole volume). | WARM-UP NON-NEGOTIABLE: Cold-weather muscles require 10–15 min warm-up before any intensity — cold tendon injury risk is significantly elevated. | Sauna recovery (traditional Scandinavian XC practice) has meaningful evidence for reducing DOMS and improving recovery between high-volume sessions.','% rises in Taper as total volume drops; absolute time similar throughout. CRITICAL AREAS: Hip flexor (skate technique sustained lateral push). Thoracic rotation (bilateral pole plant requires full thoracic mobility — skiers who restrict rotation lose power at every cycle). Shoulder posterior capsule (high bilateral pole volume). WARM-UP NON-NEGOTIABLE: Cold-weather muscles require 10–15 min warm-up before any intensity — cold tendon injury risk is significantly elevated. Sauna recovery (traditional Scandinavian XC practice) has meaningful evidence for reducing DOMS and improving recovery between high-volume sessions.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
