  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (ICF Competition)','D-010','Kayaking','Primary (*Conditional — K-variant)',83.0,90.0,84.0,90.0,84.0,90.0,87.0,93.0,'Marathon paddling K-variant. ICF-format: 5–6 paddle sessions/week. Long session: 90–120 min base; 2–3 hrs build/peak. KEY SESSIONS: (1) Threshold intervals — 5–10×3–5 min at race pace with 90-sec recovery; primary quality session in build/peak. (2) Long aerobic paddle — 2–3 hrs at Zone 2, fueling rehearsal. (3) Group tactics — drafting/wash-riding sessions 2×/week in build/peak (significant energy saving — must be trained). PORTAGE-SPECIFIC: Portage entry/exit speed is practiced separately (see Portage row). Final 500–1000m sprint: add race-pace sprint finishes to the last 5 min of threshold sessions in peak.','prompt_required','Marathon paddling K-variant.','ICF-format: 5–6 paddle sessions/week. | Long session: 90–120 min base; | 2–3 hrs build/peak. | KEY SESSIONS: (1) Threshold intervals — 5–10×3–5 min at race pace with 90-sec recovery; | primary quality session in build/peak. | (2) Long aerobic paddle — 2–3 hrs at Zone 2, fueling rehearsal. | (3) Group tactics — drafting/wash-riding sessions 2×/week in build/peak (significant energy saving — must be trained). | PORTAGE-SPECIFIC: Portage entry/exit speed is practiced separately (see Portage row). | Final 500–1000m sprint: add race-pace sprint finishes to the last 5 min of threshold sessions in peak.','Marathon paddling K-variant. ICF-format: 5–6 paddle sessions/week. Long session: 90–120 min base; 2–3 hrs build/peak. KEY SESSIONS: (1) Threshold intervals — 5–10×3–5 min at race pace with 90-sec recovery; primary quality session in build/peak. (2) Long aerobic paddle — 2–3 hrs at Zone 2, fueling rehearsal. (3) Group tactics — drafting/wash-riding sessions 2×/week in build/peak (significant energy saving — must be trained). PORTAGE-SPECIFIC: Portage entry/exit speed is practiced separately (see Portage row). Final 500–1000m sprint: add race-pace sprint finishes to the last 5 min of threshold sessions in peak.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (ICF Competition)','D-011','Canoeing','Primary (*Conditional — C-variant)',83.0,90.0,84.0,90.0,84.0,90.0,87.0,93.0,'Marathon paddling C-variant (single-blade). Athlete chooses K or C variant per their race format.','prompt_required','Marathon paddling C-variant (single-blade).','Athlete chooses K or C variant per their race format.','Marathon paddling C-variant (single-blade). Athlete chooses K or C variant per their race format.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (ICF Competition)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',6.0,8.0,4.0,6.0,3.0,5.0,2.0,3.0,'SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Rotator cuff health (mandatory — bilateral high-volume paddle stroke = overuse risk). Core stability (long-duration seated paddle position). Single-leg hip strength (portage running). Lat/rhomboid pull strength (paddle power). AVOID: Heavy pressing movements in peak — compete with shoulder recovery. Collagen + Vit C pre-session (15g + 50mg) — tendon support for wrist and elbow during high-volume phases.','included','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','FOCUS: Rotator cuff health (mandatory — bilateral high-volume paddle stroke = overuse risk). | Core stability (long-duration seated paddle position). | Single-leg hip strength (portage running). | Lat/rhomboid pull strength (paddle power). | AVOID: Heavy pressing movements in peak — compete with shoulder recovery. | Collagen + Vit C pre-session (15g + 50mg) — tendon support for wrist and elbow during high-volume phases.','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Rotator cuff health (mandatory — bilateral high-volume paddle stroke = overuse risk). Core stability (long-duration seated paddle position). Single-leg hip strength (portage running). Lat/rhomboid pull strength (paddle power). AVOID: Heavy pressing movements in peak — compete with shoulder recovery. Collagen + Vit C pre-session (15g + 50mg) — tendon support for wrist and elbow during high-volume phases.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (ICF Competition)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',3.0,5.0,3.0,5.0,3.0,5.0,5.0,8.0,'% rises in Taper as total volume drops; absolute time similar throughout. CRITICAL AREAS: Wrist/forearm extensor stretching (post every paddle session — primary overuse prevention). Hip flexor stretch (seated paddle position). Thoracic rotation (bilateral paddle stroke requires thoracic mobility). Shoulder posterior capsule stretch. CWI forearms (10 min at 11–15°C) if lateral epicondylitis developing.','included','% rises in Taper as total volume drops;','absolute time similar throughout. | CRITICAL AREAS: Wrist/forearm extensor stretching (post every paddle session — primary overuse prevention). | Hip flexor stretch (seated paddle position). | Thoracic rotation (bilateral paddle stroke requires thoracic mobility). | Shoulder posterior capsule stretch. | CWI forearms (10 min at 11–15°C) if lateral epicondylitis developing.','% rises in Taper as total volume drops; absolute time similar throughout. CRITICAL AREAS: Wrist/forearm extensor stretching (post every paddle session — primary overuse prevention). Hip flexor stretch (seated paddle position). Thoracic rotation (bilateral paddle stroke requires thoracic mobility). Shoulder posterior capsule stretch. CWI forearms (10 min at 11–15°C) if lateral epicondylitis developing.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (ICF Competition)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','—',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–12 hrs | BUILD: 10–14 hrs | PEAK: 11–15 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs  ICF competition is the higher-intensity sub-format — intervals and group tactics sessions take priority over raw volume. PADDLING: 5–6 sessions/week peak. Off-water: portage running + strength complement. 80/20 INTENSITY: applies to paddling — 80% Zone 2 aerobic, 20% threshold/race-pace. The most common error is all interval work with no long aerobic base session — saddle time and aerobic engine suffer.','included','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–12 hrs | BUILD: 10–14 hrs | PEAK: 11–15 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs','ICF competition is the higher-intensity sub-format — intervals and group tactics sessions take priority over raw volume. | PADDLING: 5–6 sessions/week peak. | Off-water: portage running + strength complement. | 80/20 INTENSITY: applies to paddling — 80% Zone 2 aerobic, 20% threshold/race-pace. | The most common error is all interval work with no long aerobic base session — saddle time and aerobic engine suffer.','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 8–12 hrs | BUILD: 10–14 hrs | PEAK: 11–15 hrs | TAPER: 5–8 hrs

ICF competition is the higher-intensity sub-format — intervals and group tactics sessions take priority over raw volume. PADDLING: 5–6 sessions/week peak. Off-water: portage running + strength complement. 80/20 INTENSITY: applies to paddling — 80% Zone 2 aerobic, 20% threshold/race-pace. The most common error is all interval work with no long aerobic base session — saddle time and aerobic engine suffer.','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (Ultra-Distance)','D-010','Kayaking','Primary (*Conditional — K-variant)',71.0,80.0,73.0,82.0,74.0,83.0,80.0,88.0,'Marathon paddling K-variant. ULTRA-DISTANCE: Training paradigm shifts from interval-dominant (ICF) to volume-dominant. PRIMARY TRAINING STIMULUS: Back-to-back long paddle days — 4–6 hrs Day 1 + 2–4 hrs Day 2 in peak phase. This is the specific ultra-distance adaptation no interval set can replicate. Volume measured in hours on water (not km). NIGHT PADDLING: Mandatory practice for non-stop events — include 1 overnight session in peak phase. Simulate event conditions: nutrition management, fatigue decision-making, hallucination awareness at 20+ hrs. NUTRITION: Train fueling on water from first long session — food management, hydration, and electrolyte intake while paddling are race-critical skills. Caloric target: 250–350 kcal/hr for multi-day events.','prompt_required','Marathon paddling K-variant.','ULTRA-DISTANCE: Training paradigm shifts from interval-dominant (ICF) to volume-dominant. | PRIMARY TRAINING STIMULUS: Back-to-back long paddle days — 4–6 hrs Day 1 + 2–4 hrs Day 2 in peak phase. | This is the specific ultra-distance adaptation no interval set can replicate. | Volume measured in hours on water (not km). | NIGHT PADDLING: Mandatory practice for non-stop events — include 1 overnight session in peak phase. | Simulate event conditions: nutrition management, fatigue decision-making, hallucination awareness at 20+ hrs. | NUTRITION: Train fueling on water from first long session — food management, hydration, and electrolyte intake while paddling are race-critical skills. | Caloric target: 250–350 kcal/hr for multi-day events.','Marathon paddling K-variant. ULTRA-DISTANCE: Training paradigm shifts from interval-dominant (ICF) to volume-dominant. PRIMARY TRAINING STIMULUS: Back-to-back long paddle days — 4–6 hrs Day 1 + 2–4 hrs Day 2 in peak phase. This is the specific ultra-distance adaptation no interval set can replicate. Volume measured in hours on water (not km). NIGHT PADDLING: Mandatory practice for non-stop events — include 1 overnight session in peak phase. Simulate event conditions: nutrition management, fatigue decision-making, hallucination awareness at 20+ hrs. NUTRITION: Train fueling on water from first long session — food management, hydration, and electrolyte intake while paddling are race-critical skills. Caloric target: 250–350 kcal/hr for multi-day events.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (Ultra-Distance)','D-011','Canoeing','Primary (*Conditional — C-variant)',71.0,80.0,73.0,82.0,74.0,83.0,80.0,88.0,'Marathon paddling C-variant (single-blade). Athlete chooses K or C variant per their race format.','prompt_required','Marathon paddling C-variant (single-blade).','Athlete chooses K or C variant per their race format.','Marathon paddling C-variant (single-blade). Athlete chooses K or C variant per their race format.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (Ultra-Distance)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',5.0,7.0,3.0,5.0,2.0,4.0,2.0,3.0,'SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2 | Build 1–2 | Peak 1 | Taper 1. Lower allocation than ICF — ultra volume leaves less recovery capacity. FOCUS: Rotator cuff health (mandatory despite volume demands). Core durability under prolonged seated load — not strength peak, but endurance. Hip flexor mobility under load (seated 10+ hrs). Grip endurance: dead hangs and farmer''s carry for portage carry simulation. SLEEP EVENTS: Strength training timing must account for back-to-back long days — never schedule strength the day before a long paddle day in build/peak.','included','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2 | Build 1–2 | Peak 1 | Taper 1.','Lower allocation than ICF — ultra volume leaves less recovery capacity. | FOCUS: Rotator cuff health (mandatory despite volume demands). | Core durability under prolonged seated load — not strength peak, but endurance. | Hip flexor mobility under load (seated 10+ hrs). | Grip endurance: dead hangs and farmer''s carry for portage carry simulation. | SLEEP EVENTS: Strength training timing must account for back-to-back long days — never schedule strength the day before a long paddle day in build/peak.','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2 | Build 1–2 | Peak 1 | Taper 1. Lower allocation than ICF — ultra volume leaves less recovery capacity. FOCUS: Rotator cuff health (mandatory despite volume demands). Core durability under prolonged seated load — not strength peak, but endurance. Hip flexor mobility under load (seated 10+ hrs). Grip endurance: dead hangs and farmer''s carry for portage carry simulation. SLEEP EVENTS: Strength training timing must account for back-to-back long days — never schedule strength the day before a long paddle day in build/peak.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (Ultra-Distance)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',4.0,6.0,4.0,6.0,4.0,6.0,5.0,8.0,'Slightly higher base allocation than ICF — ultra-distance back-to-back days require more deliberate recovery between sessions. CRITICAL AREAS: Same as ICF plus: Lower back (prolonged seated position for 10+ hrs — hip flexor + lumbar stretching after every session ≥3 hrs). Neck and shoulder (sustained paddle position). Leg elevation (20–30 min post-long-paddle — venous return after stationary effort). SLEEP: Primary recovery tool for ultra-distance athletes training 15+ hrs/week. Sleep deprivation training (1 overnight session in peak) should be followed by a full recovery day.','included','Slightly higher base allocation than ICF — ultra-distance back-to-back days require more deliberate recovery between ses','CRITICAL AREAS: Same as ICF plus: Lower back (prolonged seated position for 10+ hrs — hip flexor + lumbar stretching after every session ≥3 hrs). | Neck and shoulder (sustained paddle position). | Leg elevation (20–30 min post-long-paddle — venous return after stationary effort). | SLEEP: Primary recovery tool for ultra-distance athletes training 15+ hrs/week. | Sleep deprivation training (1 overnight session in peak) should be followed by a full recovery day.','Slightly higher base allocation than ICF — ultra-distance back-to-back days require more deliberate recovery between sessions. CRITICAL AREAS: Same as ICF plus: Lower back (prolonged seated position for 10+ hrs — hip flexor + lumbar stretching after every session ≥3 hrs). Neck and shoulder (sustained paddle position). Leg elevation (20–30 min post-long-paddle — venous return after stationary effort). SLEEP: Primary recovery tool for ultra-distance athletes training 15+ hrs/week. Sleep deprivation training (1 overnight session in peak) should be followed by a full recovery day.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Canoe / Kayak Marathon (Ultra-Distance)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','—',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 10–14 hrs | BUILD: 14–18 hrs | PEAK: 16–22 hrs | TAPER: 6–9 hrs  Ultra-distance volumes rival ultra running in peak phase. Back-to-back long paddle days (included in PEAK) will be the highest-load training unit — plan the week around them. SLEEP DEPRIVATION SESSION: Include 1 overnight paddle in peak phase if targeting non-stop events (DW, Yukon). This session is unique — do not replace with intervals. NUTRITION DURING TRAINING: Every session ≥3 hrs must include fueling practice at race cadence. The gut must be trained to accept 250–350 kcal/hr while paddling.','included','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 10–14 hrs | BUILD: 14–18 hrs | PEAK: 16–22 hrs | TAPER: 6–9 hrs','Ultra-distance volumes rival ultra running in peak phase. | Back-to-back long paddle days (included in PEAK) will be the highest-load training unit — plan the week around them. | SLEEP DEPRIVATION SESSION: Include 1 overnight paddle in peak phase if targeting non-stop events (DW, Yukon). | This session is unique — do not replace with intervals. | NUTRITION DURING TRAINING: Every session ≥3 hrs must include fueling practice at race cadence. | The gut must be trained to accept 250–350 kcal/hr while paddling.','WEEKLY TARGET HOURS: BASE: 10–14 hrs | BUILD: 14–18 hrs | PEAK: 16–22 hrs | TAPER: 6–9 hrs

Ultra-distance volumes rival ultra running in peak phase. Back-to-back long paddle days (included in PEAK) will be the highest-load training unit — plan the week around them. SLEEP DEPRIVATION SESSION: Include 1 overnight paddle in peak phase if targeting non-stop events (DW, Yukon). This session is unique — do not replace with intervals. NUTRITION DURING TRAINING: Every session ≥3 hrs must include fueling practice at race cadence. The gut must be trained to accept 250–350 kcal/hr while paddling.','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Open Water Marathon Swimming (10km / Olympic Distance)','D-004','Swimming','Primary',83.0,90.0,83.0,90.0,83.0,90.0,85.0,92.0,'10KM FOCUS. TRAINING MIX: Base/Build: 60–70% pool + 30–40% OW. Peak: 50% pool + 50% OW. POOL SESSIONS: Threshold sets (6–10×400m at race pace). Long aerobic (4–6km steady). Technique work (catch, high-elbow, bilateral breathing). OW SESSIONS: Long OW builds 6km base → 8km build → 8–10km peak. FEEDING PRACTICE mandatory from first long OW session — pontoon roll-receive technique (roll on back, receive cup, drink, roll forward) takes 15–20 repetitions to automate. Race pace: ~80% max effort, sustained 2 hrs — not sprint pacing. DRAFTING: Pack position dynamics persist over full 10km (unlike triathlon 1.5km swim). Practice sustained tactical positioning in group swims.','included','10KM FOCUS.','TRAINING MIX: Base/Build: 60–70% pool + 30–40% OW. | Peak: 50% pool + 50% OW. | POOL SESSIONS: Threshold sets (6–10×400m at race pace). | Long aerobic (4–6km steady). | Technique work (catch, high-elbow, bilateral breathing). | OW SESSIONS: Long OW builds 6km base → 8km build → 8–10km peak. | FEEDING PRACTICE mandatory from first long OW session — pontoon roll-receive technique (roll on back, receive cup, drink, roll forward) takes 15–20 repetitions to automate. | Race pace: ~80% max effort, sustained 2 hrs — not sprint pacing. | DRAFTING: Pack position dynamics persist over full 10km (unlike triathlon 1.5km swim). | Practice sustained tactical positioning in group swims.','10KM FOCUS. TRAINING MIX: Base/Build: 60–70% pool + 30–40% OW. Peak: 50% pool + 50% OW. POOL SESSIONS: Threshold sets (6–10×400m at race pace). Long aerobic (4–6km steady). Technique work (catch, high-elbow, bilateral breathing). OW SESSIONS: Long OW builds 6km base → 8km build → 8–10km peak. FEEDING PRACTICE mandatory from first long OW session — pontoon roll-receive technique (roll on back, receive cup, drink, roll forward) takes 15–20 repetitions to automate. Race pace: ~80% max effort, sustained 2 hrs — not sprint pacing. DRAFTING: Pack position dynamics persist over full 10km (unlike triathlon 1.5km swim). Practice sustained tactical positioning in group swims.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Open Water Marathon Swimming (10km / Olympic Distance)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',6.0,9.0,5.0,7.0,4.0,6.0,2.0,4.0,'SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Rotator cuff antagonists — external rotation (prone Y, band pull-apart) mandatory to counterbalance internal-rotation dominance of freestyle. Thoracic extension (counteracts forward-head position from sighting). Core stability (hip engagement transfers to kick). Ankle plantar flexion strength and flexibility (kick economy). PADDLE CAUTION: Regular swim paddles in training significantly associated with shoulder overuse injury (PMC5983428, p=0.014). Limit paddles to 1×/week maximum.','included','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1.','FOCUS: Rotator cuff antagonists — external rotation (prone Y, band pull-apart) mandatory to counterbalance internal-rotation dominance of freestyle. | Thoracic extension (counteracts forward-head position from sighting). | Core stability (hip engagement transfers to kick). | Ankle plantar flexion strength and flexibility (kick economy). | PADDLE CAUTION: Regular swim paddles in training significantly associated with shoulder overuse injury (PMC5983428, p=0.014). | Limit paddles to 1×/week maximum.','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Rotator cuff antagonists — external rotation (prone Y, band pull-apart) mandatory to counterbalance internal-rotation dominance of freestyle. Thoracic extension (counteracts forward-head position from sighting). Core stability (hip engagement transfers to kick). Ankle plantar flexion strength and flexibility (kick economy). PADDLE CAUTION: Regular swim paddles in training significantly associated with shoulder overuse injury (PMC5983428, p=0.014). Limit paddles to 1×/week maximum.','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Open Water Marathon Swimming (10km / Olympic Distance)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',4.0,6.0,4.0,6.0,4.0,6.0,5.0,8.0,'% rises in Taper as total volume drops; absolute time similar throughout. CRITICAL AREAS: Shoulder posterior capsule (cross-body stretch post every session — reduces impingement risk with high bilateral volume). Thoracic rotation and extension (sighting load on cervical spine). Ankle and foot plantar flexion (kick flexibility directly affects propulsion efficiency). POST COLD OW SESSION: Warm shower immediately, warm beverage, monitor for hypothermia (shivering >30 min post-exit = seek warmth). Cold water tolerance is trainable but don''t skip the warm recovery protocol.','included','% rises in Taper as total volume drops;','absolute time similar throughout. | CRITICAL AREAS: Shoulder posterior capsule (cross-body stretch post every session — reduces impingement risk with high bilateral volume). | Thoracic rotation and extension (sighting load on cervical spine). | Ankle and foot plantar flexion (kick flexibility directly affects propulsion efficiency). | POST COLD OW SESSION: Warm shower immediately, warm beverage, monitor for hypothermia (shivering >30 min post-exit = seek warmth). | Cold water tolerance is trainable but don''t skip the warm recovery protocol.','% rises in Taper as total volume drops; absolute time similar throughout. CRITICAL AREAS: Shoulder posterior capsule (cross-body stretch post every session — reduces impingement risk with high bilateral volume). Thoracic rotation and extension (sighting load on cervical spine). Ankle and foot plantar flexion (kick flexibility directly affects propulsion efficiency). POST COLD OW SESSION: Warm shower immediately, warm beverage, monitor for hypothermia (shivering >30 min post-exit = seek warmth). Cold water tolerance is trainable but don''t skip the warm recovery protocol.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Open Water Marathon Swimming (10km / Olympic Distance)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','—',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET VOLUME (km/wk): BASE: 30–45 km | BUILD: 40–55 km | PEAK: 45–60 km | TAPER: 20–30 km  Volume measured in km (standard across OW swimming — pool and OW combined). SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 6–8 | Build 6–8 | Peak 5–7 | Taper 4–5. Elite 10km: 60–80 km/wk year-round. Recreational competitive 10km: 30–50 km/wk peak. COLD WATER ACCLIMATIZATION: Begin 8–10 weeks before cold-water race (below 18°C). Short exposures (10–15 min at target temperature) building to 45–60 min. Don''t skip — hypothermia is preventable with specific training.','included','WEEKLY TARGET VOLUME (km/wk): BASE: 30–45 km | BUILD: 40–55 km | PEAK: 45–60 km | TAPER: 20–30 km','Volume measured in km (standard across OW swimming — pool and OW combined). | SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 6–8 | Build 6–8 | Peak 5–7 | Taper 4–5. | Elite 10km: 60–80 km/wk year-round. | Recreational competitive 10km: 30–50 km/wk peak. | COLD WATER ACCLIMATIZATION: Begin 8–10 weeks before cold-water race (below 18°C). | Short exposures (10–15 min at target temperature) building to 45–60 min. | Don''t skip — hypothermia is preventable with specific training.','WEEKLY TARGET VOLUME (km/wk): BASE: 30–45 km | BUILD: 40–55 km | PEAK: 45–60 km | TAPER: 20–30 km

Volume measured in km (standard across OW swimming — pool and OW combined). SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 6–8 | Build 6–8 | Peak 5–7 | Taper 4–5. Elite 10km: 60–80 km/wk year-round. Recreational competitive 10km: 30–50 km/wk peak. COLD WATER ACCLIMATIZATION: Begin 8–10 weeks before cold-water race (below 18°C). Short exposures (10–15 min at target temperature) building to 45–60 min. Don''t skip — hypothermia is preventable with specific training.','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Open Water Marathon Swimming (25km / Ultra Distance)','D-004','Swimming','Primary',82.0,90.0,82.0,90.0,82.0,90.0,84.0,92.0,'25KM FOCUS. Higher volume than 10km — the primary differentiator is sustained aerobic capacity and cold-water management. TRAINING MIX: Base: 65% pool + 35% OW. Build/Peak: 55% pool + 45% OW. POOL SESSIONS: Long aerobic (6–8km steady at race pace feel). Threshold sets (4–6×500m at race pace). OW SESSIONS: Long OW builds 8km base → 12km build → 14–18km peak. COLD WATER ACCLIMATIZATION (mandatory if race below 18°C): Begin 8–10 weeks before race. Progress: 10 min at target temperature → 20–30 min → 45–60 min → race-simulation (1–2 hrs in cold). Cold-water feeding: practice eating and drinking in cold water specifically — swallowing is impaired by cold, and decision-making slows. CHANNEL SWIMS: Include one 5–6 hr training swim in peak phase. Night swimming practice required for events starting at night or extending past dark.','included','25KM FOCUS.','Higher volume than 10km — the primary differentiator is sustained aerobic capacity and cold-water management. | TRAINING MIX: Base: 65% pool + 35% OW. | Build/Peak: 55% pool + 45% OW. | POOL SESSIONS: Long aerobic (6–8km steady at race pace feel). | Threshold sets (4–6×500m at race pace). | OW SESSIONS: Long OW builds 8km base → 12km build → 14–18km peak. | COLD WATER ACCLIMATIZATION (mandatory if race below 18°C): Begin 8–10 weeks before race. | Progress: 10 min at target temperature → 20–30 min → 45–60 min → race-simulation (1–2 hrs in cold). | Cold-water feeding: practice eating and drinking in cold water specifically — swallowing is impaired by cold, and decision-making slows. | CHANNEL SWIMS: Include one 5–6 hr training swim in peak phase. | Night swimming practice required for events starting at night or extending past dark.','25KM FOCUS. Higher volume than 10km — the primary differentiator is sustained aerobic capacity and cold-water management. TRAINING MIX: Base: 65% pool + 35% OW. Build/Peak: 55% pool + 45% OW. POOL SESSIONS: Long aerobic (6–8km steady at race pace feel). Threshold sets (4–6×500m at race pace). OW SESSIONS: Long OW builds 8km base → 12km build → 14–18km peak. COLD WATER ACCLIMATIZATION (mandatory if race below 18°C): Begin 8–10 weeks before race. Progress: 10 min at target temperature → 20–30 min → 45–60 min → race-simulation (1–2 hrs in cold). Cold-water feeding: practice eating and drinking in cold water specifically — swallowing is impaired by cold, and decision-making slows. CHANNEL SWIMS: Include one 5–6 hr training swim in peak phase. Night swimming practice required for events starting at night or extending past dark.',NULL,'0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Open Water Marathon Swimming (25km / Ultra Distance)',NULL,'Strength Training','Accessory',5.0,8.0,4.0,6.0,3.0,5.0,2.0,4.0,'Same structure as 10km, with slightly higher base allocation to support the greater volume load. SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Rotator cuff antagonists (same as 10km — higher bilateral volume = higher shoulder overuse risk). Core. Ankle flexibility. ADDITIONAL FOR 25km: Neck strengthening — sighting demand over 5+ hrs is substantial; cervical spine fatigue is a real performance variable in long OW events. Practice supported head position exercises. PADDLE CAUTION: Same as 10km — limit paddles to 1×/week max (PMC5983428).','included','Same structure as 10km, with slightly higher base allocation to support the greater volume load.','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. | FOCUS: Rotator cuff antagonists (same as 10km — higher bilateral volume = higher shoulder overuse risk). | Core. | Ankle flexibility. | ADDITIONAL FOR 25km: Neck strengthening — sighting demand over 5+ hrs is substantial; | cervical spine fatigue is a real performance variable in long OW events. | Practice supported head position exercises. | PADDLE CAUTION: Same as 10km — limit paddles to 1×/week max (PMC5983428).','Same structure as 10km, with slightly higher base allocation to support the greater volume load. SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 2–3 | Build 2 | Peak 1–2 | Taper 1. FOCUS: Rotator cuff antagonists (same as 10km — higher bilateral volume = higher shoulder overuse risk). Core. Ankle flexibility. ADDITIONAL FOR 25km: Neck strengthening — sighting demand over 5+ hrs is substantial; cervical spine fatigue is a real performance variable in long OW events. Practice supported head position exercises. PADDLE CAUTION: Same as 10km — limit paddles to 1×/week max (PMC5983428).','strength','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Open Water Marathon Swimming (25km / Ultra Distance)',NULL,'Mobility / Recovery','Foundation',4.0,6.0,4.0,6.0,4.0,6.0,5.0,8.0,'% rises in Taper. CRITICAL AREAS: Shoulder posterior capsule and thoracic extension (same as 10km, higher volume = greater demand). Neck rotation — 5+ hr sighting load. POST COLD OW SESSION (especially critical for 25km prep): Immediate warm shower + warm beverage + change out of wet clothing. Monitor for delayed hypothermia (shivering 45+ min post-exit warrants additional warming and rest). SLEEP: Primary recovery tool at this training volume (55–75 km/wk peak). Sleep deprivation after back-to-back long OW sessions mimics the cognitive state of race-day fatigue — useful training data, not a target state to maintain.','included','% rises in Taper.','CRITICAL AREAS: Shoulder posterior capsule and thoracic extension (same as 10km, higher volume = greater demand). | Neck rotation — 5+ hr sighting load. | POST COLD OW SESSION (especially critical for 25km prep): Immediate warm shower + warm beverage + change out of wet clothing. | Monitor for delayed hypothermia (shivering 45+ min post-exit warrants additional warming and rest). | SLEEP: Primary recovery tool at this training volume (55–75 km/wk peak). | Sleep deprivation after back-to-back long OW sessions mimics the cognitive state of race-day fatigue — useful training data, not a target state to maintain.','% rises in Taper. CRITICAL AREAS: Shoulder posterior capsule and thoracic extension (same as 10km, higher volume = greater demand). Neck rotation — 5+ hr sighting load. POST COLD OW SESSION (especially critical for 25km prep): Immediate warm shower + warm beverage + change out of wet clothing. Monitor for delayed hypothermia (shivering 45+ min post-exit warrants additional warming and rest). SLEEP: Primary recovery tool at this training volume (55–75 km/wk peak). Sleep deprivation after back-to-back long OW sessions mimics the cognitive state of race-day fatigue — useful training data, not a target state to maintain.','mobility','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz),
  ('Open Water Marathon Swimming (25km / Ultra Distance)',NULL,'WEEKLY TOTAL TARGET','—',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WEEKLY TARGET VOLUME (km/wk): BASE: 35–50 km | BUILD: 45–65 km | PEAK: 55–75 km | TAPER: 25–35 km  SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 6–8 | Build 6–8 | Peak 6–8 | Taper 4–5. Higher volume than 10km at every phase — the 25km demands greater aerobic base and cold-water endurance. Elite 25km: 70–100 km/wk peak. CHANNEL SWIM PREP: 60–100 km/wk peak (extreme — cold-water tolerance and mental endurance demand extreme volume exposure). TAPER: 2 weeks recommended (vs. 1 for 10km). Final long OW session: 2 weeks before race. Last cold-water acclimatization session: 10–14 days before race (allow physiological adaptation to complete before event).','included','WEEKLY TARGET VOLUME (km/wk): BASE: 35–50 km | BUILD: 45–65 km | PEAK: 55–75 km | TAPER: 25–35 km','SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 6–8 | Build 6–8 | Peak 6–8 | Taper 4–5. | Higher volume than 10km at every phase — the 25km demands greater aerobic base and cold-water endurance. | Elite 25km: 70–100 km/wk peak. | CHANNEL SWIM PREP: 60–100 km/wk peak (extreme — cold-water tolerance and mental endurance demand extreme volume exposure). | TAPER: 2 weeks recommended (vs. | 1 for 10km). | Final long OW session: 2 weeks before race. | Last cold-water acclimatization session: 10–14 days before race (allow physiological adaptation to complete before event).','WEEKLY TARGET VOLUME (km/wk): BASE: 35–50 km | BUILD: 45–65 km | PEAK: 55–75 km | TAPER: 25–35 km

SESSIONS/WEEK: Base 6–8 | Build 6–8 | Peak 6–8 | Taper 4–5. Higher volume than 10km at every phase — the 25km demands greater aerobic base and cold-water endurance. Elite 25km: 70–100 km/wk peak. CHANNEL SWIM PREP: 60–100 km/wk peak (extreme — cold-water tolerance and mental endurance demand extreme volume exposure). TAPER: 2 weeks recommended (vs. 1 for 10km). Final long OW session: 2 weeks before race. Last cold-water acclimatization session: 10–14 days before race (allow physiological adaptation to complete before event).','weekly_total','0A-v1.6.6','2026-06-10T17:40:05.453426+00:00'::timestamptz);
